<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy to Meet Taliban Leaders Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Special Envoy
Nobert Holl will hold talks on Thursday with the leaders of the
Afghan Islamic Taliban militia to continue his mediation mission
for peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be held in Kandahar, the stronghold of the
Taliban in southern Afghanistan, about 450 kilometers southwest of
Kabul.
Holl's visit will be his second to the war-torn country in just
three days.
</P>
<P>
Holl is expected to brief the Taliban about the outcome of his
latest talks with the anti-Taliban alliance led mainly by Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik and Afghanistan's former military chief Ahmad
Masood.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Holl visited Mazar-e-Sharif, the base of the
anti-Taliban alliance some 300 kilometers northwest of Kabul, and
held talks with the leaders of the alliance on peace proposals
including the formation of a political commission and exchange of
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Malik ruled out the possibility of releasing
the prisoners of the Taliban militia before a negotiated
settlement of the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who had briefly sided with the Taliban by allowing them
into northern Afghanistan in May, detained some 1,000 Taliban men
when he broke rank with the militia and chased them out of
Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance has proposed to set up a joint
political commission to address issues including cease-fire and a
broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia have been persistent in demanding the
release of their prisoners while advocating that the political
commission should be broad-based with representation from all
Afghan groups, not just the northern alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
