<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Pound to Push Industry into Recession, CBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The strong pound has sent
Britain's export-dependent regions into deep gloom and threatens a
nationwide recession in manufacturing, the Confederation of
British industry (CBI) warned.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing orders stagnated or fell in five out of the UK's
11 regions in the four months to July, according to the CBI's
latest regional survey.
</P>
<P>
The hardest-hit region was Wales, which a year ago was leading
a manufacturing renaissance. Business assessment fell sharply on
the back of a steep drop in orders.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts warned that manufacturing is in danger of
tipping back into recession, after official figures showed that
output in the sector is basically flat.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) reported Tuesday a 0.1
percent fall in manufacturing production between the first and
second quarters of this year.
</P>
<P>
About half of all manufacturing sectors saw production fall in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Production of cars fell by 3.1 percent between the first and
second quarters, leading to an overall decline of 1.1 percent in
durable goods output.
</P>
<P>
Output of non-durable goods output also fell by 1.1 percent,
with clothing, footwear and food all showing significant declines.
</P>
<P>
Marian Bell, treasury economist at the Royal Bank of Scotland,
said manufacturing was suffering from the "sterling effect" and
being hit by imports.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Loynes, of HSBC markets, said: "There must be a real
danger of a further fall in output in the next quarter, putting
manufacturing technically back into recession." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
