<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Asks EC to Re-probe into GSP Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will ask the European
Commission (EC) to send another delegation to Dhaka to
re-investigate the certificate cases under the General System of
Preference (GSP), according to official sources here.
</P>
<P>
The EC imposed some restrictions on Bangladesh's export of
ready-made garments late last year on a plea that thousands of
forged GSP certificates were issued to some exporters who did not
abide by the rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been enjoying the GSP facilities in the European
Union countries since 1986 with duty-free entry without any quota
restrictions. But the products must be made of indigenous
materials to get the facilities.
</P>
<P>
The EC on Sunday said in a letter to Dhaka that it will accept
some derogation from the rules of origin in importing Bangladeshi
garment products only on condition of canceling the erroneous GSP
certificates issued between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government, however, wants further
investigation into the matter, saying the grounds on which the EC
is demanding cancellation of some certificates are not convincing.
</P>
<P>
"Most exporters are the victims of misunderstanding," said an
official of the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Tofail Ahmed will send the request letters,
which cite the social implications likely to be created following
the ban on the export of ready-made garments, to the EC for a
sympathetic consideration, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"The main victims will be the female garment workers because
the ban will lead to closure of at least 100 garment units,"
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Out of a total of 270,000 million garment workers, about
130,000 female workers will lose jobs immediately, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
