<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Lowers Key Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank said
today it will further cut its overnight borrowing rate from 20 to
18 percent Thursday considering a gradually-stabilizing foreign
currency market.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth time for the Central Bank to cut its key
borrowing rate on one-day reverse repurchase papers (RRPs) since
July 11 when it allowed the effective depreciation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
The RRPs are debt papers used by the Central Bank to mop up
excess money in the financial system. It is an agreement that the
Central Bank can borrow money from banks using its inventory of
government securities and buy them back at a premium sometime in
the future.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also decided to cut its overnight lending rate
from 25 to 22 percent effective Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank hiked its overnight borrowing rate to a
two-and-a-half-year high of 32 percent on July 10 in a bid to
repulse speculative attacks on the peso.
</P>
<P>
The country's commercial banks are expected to follow the
Central Bank to cut their hefty interest rates, which economists
warned would imperil sustained economic growth if kept unchanged
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
The weighted average exchange rate between the peso and the
U.S. dollar was pegged at 28.512 pesos to one dollar today at the
Philippine Dealing System (PDS), the electronic inter-bank
currency exchange system. The rate is much higher than its record
low of 29.45 registered on July 11 at the PDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
