<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan Consult on Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati said here today that the Afghan issue should be
resolved through peaceful means, adding that Iran is ready to
cooperate with the neighboring states on the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
Velayati made the remarks at the meeting with visiting
Pakistani Deputy Foreign Minister Iftikhar Morshed.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan crisis has become the bone of contention in
Tehran-Islamabad relations.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said the current situation in Afghanistan has
negative and adverse impact on the national security of the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister said Iran supports establishment
of a broad-based government of Afghanistan and resolving the
Afghan crisis through peaceful means which is possible in case of
non-interference of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Velayati was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying
"Iran is ready to cooperate with the neighboring states in this
respect."
</P>
<P>
However, he added, the Afghan issue should not have negative
impact on Tehran-Islamabad friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Morshed outlined his country's efforts to
encourage the Islamic militia Taliban in Afghanistan to sit at
the negotiating table to solve the plight of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Morshed, also Pakistani special representative for the Afghan
affairs, voiced at the meeting Islamabad's willingness to
cooperate with Tehran in order to bring closer the views of the
belligerent parties in Afghanistan and help resolve the Afghan
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
