<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, Indonesia Selected for Illness Control Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and Indonesia have been
selected as the sites for carrying out an experiment on integrated
management of childhood illness (IMCI), World Health Organization
(WHO) representative to Nepal Harry Feirmann said here today.
</P>
<P>
Feirmann made the remarks when addressing the 12-day
Inter-Country Training for Consultants of Integrated Management of
Childhood Illness, jointly organized by the WHO and the Nepali
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
About 31 doctors from Nepal, Bangladesh, India, Bhutan,
Indonesia, Sweden and Ethiopia are participating in the training.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO estimates, more than 115,000 Nepalese children
die before their fifth birthday and 70 percent of them succumb to
diarrhea, pneumonia, malnutrition, malaria and measles.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Nepali Health Ministry Sriram Poudel said the
IMCI program would be helpful in improving the performance of the
health workers.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Health Minister Radha Krishna Mainali said one of the
major targets of the Nepali government is to reduce the infant
mortality rate from 79 to 50 per thousand and the under-age-five
mortality rate from 118 to 70 per thousand by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Reducing deaths caused by diarrhea, pneumonia, measles, malaria
and malnutrition is an essential part of this endeavor, he added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
