<HEADLINE> Lesotho Reconfirms General Election Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government
today denied claims by opposition parties that the general
election date had been shifted from January to September next
year.
</P>
<P>
"We wish to hold this general elections by January,
particularly in that month because the day is long and it's warm.
This is done to avoid people standing in long queues in winter
months," acting Constitutional Affairs Minister Monyane Moleleki
said in Maseru, capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, the end of the five-year term of Lesotho's
National Assembly is June 3, 1998, and the constitution provides
that an election should be held within this term.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Malebo, spokesman for opposition parties, said earlier
that the newly established party, Lesotho Congress for Democracy
(LCD) headed by Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle was very much likely to
delay the election date.
</P>
<P>
As LCD needed enough time to set up its structures and prepare
for the election, "we believe that they want to stretch the
election date to September," Malebo said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mokhehle in June quit the ruling Basutoland
Congress Party and continued to rule through his new party, LCD.
Lesotho's opposition parties have strongly denounced Mokhehle's
action and demanded for early general elections to change the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
