<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Reported in Manila-Leftists Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
insurgent leftist National Democratic Front (NDF) have made
significant progress in their stormy peace talks held in the Dutch
city of The Hague, local television reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from the NDF and the government have reached an
agreement on the humanitarian law in the Philippines, Jose Sison,
consultant of the NDF peace panel, told the local Sky Cable
television by telephone from The Hague.
</P>
<P>
Sison said the two sides had solved their differences over
humanitarian law and human rights, adding that the signing of the
agreement paved the way for forging a final peace agreement
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
But at his weekly press conference today, President Fidel Ramos
said he had not yet received an official report from the
government panel on the talks.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, however, expressed optimism that the NDF and the
government will soon enter into negotiations for a final
settlement of the group's 28 years of insurgency in the country.
</P>
<P>
The NDF is a leftist alliance led by the Communist Party of the
Philippines, which was chaired by Sison. Sison exiled himself to
the Netherlands after military setbacks the NDF suffered in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
The NDF's military wing, the New People's Army, has fought the
government for about 28 years. The strength of the New People's
Army has been reduced to about 50,000-80,000 people after the
military launched massive operations against it in the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
