<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Northern Cyprus Sign Agreement on Partial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and northern Cyprus today
signed an agreement to establish a Partnership Council in a bid to
provide partial integration on security, defense and foreign
policy and full integration on economy and finance.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Nicosia by northern Cyprus
official Taner Etkin and Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, who
paid a one-day working visit to the region, according to a report
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Northern Cyprus leader Rauf Denktash described the agreement
as a "historical decision" and stressed the importance of the
agreement for northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Cem said that the establishment of the
Partnership Council was important and that they brought Turkey's
respect and guarantee before the second round direct talks
between Denktash and Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides in the
Swiss town of Montreux.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint statement issued after the talks between
Turkish and northern Cyprus officials said the European Union (EU)
Commission's recent decision about its membership expansion had a
negative effect on a solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission announced last month that Cyprus was
included in the ranks of the prospective EU membership
candidates, triggering strong reaction from Turkey and northern
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that solution process should be based on
political equality of Turkish Cypriot side and equal sovereignty,
stressing that the balance, stemming from the 1960 agreement
signed between Turkey and Greece, should be preserved.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a breakaway
state" the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which
has only been recognized by Turkey. At present, about 30,000
Turkish troops are stationed in northern part of the island to
safeguard the security of the Turkish Cypriots there.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash met last month at Troutbeck near New York
in the first round of direct talks sponsored by the U.N. for the
first time in nearly three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
