<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik President: Situation in Afghanistan Treats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The worsening situation in
Afghanistan is posing a threat to Tajikistan's national security,
Tajik President Emomali Rakhamonov stated in Dushanbe on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Tajikistan's Capital Dushanbe, the
president expressed the anxiety about his country's security
during the talks with U.S. Senator Charles Robb, who is on a tour
of nine Caucasian and Central Asian states, including Pakistan and
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
It said that the result of his tour will be used to work out
recommendations on the United States' cooperation with those
countries in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Tajik presidential spokesman Zafar Saidov quoted president
Rakhamonov as saying that the situation in Afghanistan is that
country's internal affair, but "we will be glad if the
reconciliation process in Afghanistan proceeds on the basis of the
Tajik scenario."
</P>
<P>
Rakhamonov noted that the scale of the illegal drug trade is
making a threat to Tajikistan's national security."It is a very
serious threat," he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that international organizations and the
United States will help Dushanbe to combat the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
"We don't grow drugs legally and don't want to become a
trans-shipping point for international drug traders, who are making
use of instability in Afghanistan and our temporary problems in a
bid to attain their dirty goals," Rakhamonov emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
