<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Airport Strikers Refuse to Resume Work, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The crisis facing Kenya's air
transport industry got worsen as the air traffic controllers in
main airports ignored a governmental order to resume work and
went on their go-slow on the fifth day today.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior airport official told Xinhua that the
go-slow will wind up soon as discussions between the controllers
and the government have been underway.
</P>
<P>
"A comprise is coming soon," said the official who refused to
be identified. But the government will not meet the controllers
50-fold wage hike demand, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
"They (the controllers) are asking an enormous figure," he
said. The strikers asked the authorities to raise their monthly
pay from about 90 U.S. Dollars to around 5,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The official also denied any relations between the on-going
go-slow and the national strike set for Friday, saying Kenyan
airport staff launch go-slow almost every year. The last one
lasted only a few days in December, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government last night declared illegal the go-slow by air
traffic controllers and employees of the Meteorological
Department. Later, Labor Minister Philip Masinde directed the
employees to resume work immediately.
</P>
<P>
But the strikers said they will continue the go-slow and even
step up their action until their demands are met.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of flights continued to be canceled, delayed, re-routed
or rescheduled in the airports at capital Nairobi, the Indian
Ocean port city of Mombasa, Kisumu ashore Lake Victoria and the
tourist resort of Malindi, 125 kilometers north of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The controllers, who gave the government a two-day ultimatum
to effect the salary increment on Monday, rejected resolutions
reached in a meeting between their managers and officials from
the Office of the President on the following day.
</P>
<P>
In view of the deteriorating situation, the national carrier,
Kenya Airways, was forced to cancel most of its international and
domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
Airport sources said flights due to land in Nairobi were being
diverted to neighboring airports in Tanzania and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Flights into Kenya were delayed in the skies for one to two
hours before they were allowed to land. Departing flights were
delayed for anywhere between three and 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
Tour operators, hotel managers and taxi drivers said they were
losing business as a result of the go-slow. Cargo and tourist
carriers are specially hard hit, with flowers for export stuck
with no chance of getting connections to their markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The go-slow increased pressure on the government hit by the
International Monetary Fund on Thursday halting a 205-million-Dollar
aid package to Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece's Inflation Drops to 5.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Greece's annual inflation dropped
slightly from 5.5 percent in June to 5.4 percent in July, the
Greek National Statistics Service (NSS) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index fell 1.9 percent in July, compared to
a 1.7 percent reduction in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The NSS attributed the only slight fall in inflation mainly to
the vegetable prices which did not drop as much this year as in
1995, when they reduced by 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
