<HEADLINE> Solana Satisfied with Russian-NATO Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana said he is pleased with the evolution of Russian-NATO
relations following the signing of the Founding Act on mutual
relations this Spring, the Interfax reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Signing of the Founding Act was a landmark, Solana said, the
act calls for the setting up of a joint permanent council which
will serve as tool for consultations, coordination and, as far as
possible and needed, for joint decision and activities in security
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
According to Solana, the council has held its first meeting in
Brussels, and another meeting, at the level of foreign ministers,
will be held in New York in September during a U.N. General
assembly session, when Russian foreign minister Yevgeny Primakov
representing Russia and Solana - NATO will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
NATO wants every field covered by the act discussed with
Russia, Solana said and hoped to early open a NATO information
office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Solana arrived in Moscow last Saturday with his wife, son and
daughter on a 10-day private visit at the invitation of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
He said that the private visit offers him the opportunity to
establish informal personal relations with Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Solana had a meeting with Russian First Deputy Prime Minister
Boris Nemtsov Monday and a private dinner with Primakov later in
the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
