<HEADLINE> Cameroon Bans Sale of Contaminated Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon has put a ban on
the sale of contaminated drugs which threaten the health of
the population in the country, the "Cameroun Tribune" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The ban came a few days ago when Health Minsiter Charles
Etoundi released two communiques, warning the public not to use
pharmaceutical products containing mold and decay substances.
</P>
<P>
The communiques also imposed a ban on sale of contaminated
drugs including lyptocodine syrop and derivatives of blood tonics
manufactured by a french biotechnological laboratory.
</P>
<P>
Local doctors are requested not to prescribe the derivatives
of blood tonics to patients, and pharmacists are urged not to
import, stockpile and distribute these drugs, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Stocks which have already gone into the market must be sent
back to the wholesalers for the eventural withdrawal and
distruction by the authorities in accordance with the communiques.
</P>
<P>
The public health authorities in Cameroon said they are
determined to allow only good quality medicaments in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
