<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Plans to Lower Drink-drive Limit by Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
considering cutting the drink-drive limit as part of a range of
options to improve road safety, according to the Department of
Transport.
</P>
<P>
The current limit is 80 milligrams of alcohol per 100
milliliters of blood, allowing most people to drink about two pint
of beer. This can be cut by almost half to only 50 milligrams,
equivalent of just one pint of beer.
</P>
<P>
The cut, which could be implemented by Christmas, signals the
most drastic attack on drink-driving since the limit was
introduced in 1967.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Department of Transport said that Australia
and France were two of the countries the government was looking
at. Both have reduced their limit to 50 milligrams per 100
milliliters.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that an average of 540 people die each year in
Britain in drink-related accidents, and the government's move
follows an 18 percent increase in the number of drink-drivers
detected last Christmas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
