<HEADLINE> British, Greek Officials Hold Talks on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British European Minister
Doug Henderson today discussed with Greece's Foreign
Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after their two-hour talks, Henderson
said that if the Cyprus issue had been resolved through a
negotiated settlement, Nicosia's accession path towards the
European Union (EU) would be much smoother.
</P>
<P>
In response, Kranidiotis said that the decision taken for the
commencement of negotiations for EU accession with the Cyprus
government six months after the inter-governmental conference must
be adhered to.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that this did not mean efforts should not be
made in the meantime for a just and viable solution of the Cyprus
problem in view of the fresh round of talks between Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash in Geneva on August 11.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British minister also praised Athens for the
contribution it made to improve the Albanian situation.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that with the help of the international community and
the Greek Government in particular, the neighboring Albania would
establish a firm constitutional position which would enable the
country to contribute to stability in the Balkan region. 
</P>
