<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriots to Exchange Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 600 Greek Cypriots will
visit the Monastery of Apostolos Andreas, patron saint of the
island at the Turkish-controlled northern part of Cyprus, on
August 15, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Presidential Commissioner for
Humanitarian Affairs Takis Christopoulos said that some 400
Turkish Cypriots will come to the southern government-controlled
areas to visit the village of Kokkina on the north-western
coast of the island.
</P>
<P>
Christopoulos said both sides will take necessary measures to
make sure that the visits take place without any problems.
</P>
<P>
He also said a second visit to the Monastery of Apostolos
Andreasfor, one of the most important religious pilgrimages in
the Greek Orthodox Church, could take place on Saint Andreas'
day, November 30.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press today, government spokesman Manolis
Christofides said the visits were agreed by Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash during
their recent meetings in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had two meetings in Nicosia last week, under
auspices of U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, to discuss humanitarian issues and reached an agreement
on missing persons during the event of Turkish military
intervention in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said "things seem to be running smoothly so
far."
</P>
<P>
The announcement of exchange of visits is seen here as a
goodwill gesture expressed by the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides just a week before the second round of direct talks will
take place in Switzerland from August 11 to 16.
</P>
<P>
Last April, a trip to Apostolos Andreas had to be canceled
after the Turkish Cypriot side insisted on vetting the list of
persons wishing to visit the Monastery.
</P>
<P>
But some 450 Turkish Cypriots crossed to southern
government-controled areas in April for a pilgrimage to Hala
Sultan Tekke mosque in Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island following
a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The people from the two sides have been prohibited to cross
the U.N.-controlled buffer zone which separates the island into
two parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
