<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Maintain Trade Sanctions on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will maintain
trade sanctions imposed on Burundi by its neighbors, which will
be lifted only when the military junta of Pierre Buyoya initiates
unconditional return to democracy in that country.
</P>
<P>
This was said today by a senior official from the Ministry for
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation here while
commenting on the words that Dar es Salaam has lifted the
sanctions on Burundi's cargo.
</P>
<P>
"No lift has been made by the government on those sanctions,
apart from the decision made by leaders of the Great Lakes region
to ease the trade sanctions," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Trade sanctions have been imposed on Burundi since July of
1996 by its neighboring countries after Buyoya took power in a
coup.
</P>
<P>
However, leaders of the Great Lakes region met in Arusha,
northern Tanzania this April and eased the sanctions to alleviate
the suffering of the vulnerable group -- women, children and the
elderly. Goods which qualify to cross to Burundi from Dar es
Salaam include fertilizers, medicines, farm implements and milk.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Sanction Committee is expected to
meet soon to review the imposed trade sanctions on Burundi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
