<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Central Bank to Intervene in Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
will intervene in the foreign exchange market whenever the need
arises, the CBK Governor Micah Cheserem said today.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here today, Cheserem said that the speed
at which the Kenyan Shilling was falling had caused great concern
following the decision by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
to halt an aid package to Kenya last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement stated, "The Shilling exchange rate to the
U.S. Dollar opened at a mean rate of 64 and rapidly depreciated
to a selling rate as low as 69."
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that several importers were rushing to pay
their foreign bills in order to minimize exchange losses while
exporters were holding back Dollars in anticipation of further
Shilling losses.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem noted that foreign investors in government treasury
bills and stocks were in the market following the IMF move,
buying foreign exchange to repatriate their investments.
</P>
<P>
The combination of the above forces has caused the current
turbulence in the foreign exchange market, the CBK governor said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to participants in the foreign exchange market to
be calm as "the government has already committed itself to managing
its expenditure within available resources".
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Shilling has depreciated by over 10 percent since
last Friday when the market received the news that the IMF
suspended the three-year Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility
to Kenya, amounting to 215 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
