<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Warns on Violation of Sanctions Against S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping
force known as ECOMOG today warned all ships and aircraft to keep
off Sierra Leone as its full sanctions against the troubled
country has begun.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG statement from Monrovia, the Liberian capital, said
any attempt of ships and planes to enter the territorial waters
and airspace of Sierra Leone will be regarded as violation of the
warning.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force will take reprisal to any ship or
aircraft that challenge the blockade, according to the warning,
which was effective from today.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone,
the warning came after the reported arrival of ships with rice
and fuel in the troubled country over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has taken actions to tighten economic embargo and
sanctions against Sierra Leone following the call of General Sani
Abacha, chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) and Nigerian head of state.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha announced "full scale embargo" on Sierra Leone
last Saturday after the collapse of talks between ECOWAS foreign
ministers and the junta's delegation in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire,
to seek ways for the junta to hand over power to the civilian
government toppled in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
The junta's strong-man, Major Johnny Koroma, announced last
Thursday that the military would not step down until 2001, which
enraged ECOWAS and led to the collapse of the talks.
</P>
<P>
According to a BBC broadcasting monitored here, the United
Nations Security Council today nodded specified sanctions against
Sierra Leona's coup leader Koroma, which diplomats said could
lead to arms and travel ban.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leadership of Sierra Leone's Kamajours in
Monrovia said fighting between its militiamen and soldiers loyal
to Koroma was continuing at a town in southeastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The military regime has sent reinforcement of men and
artillery to the area six miles west of the Liberian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
