<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Continue Strong Growth, Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's economy will grow 3.5
percent this year and 3.7 percent next year, Bank of Montreal
predicted today.
</P>
<P>
The economy is posting its strongest sustained growth of the
1990s and will continue to outperform in an environment of low
interest rates and low inflation, Canada's third largest bank said
in its mid-year economic review.
</P>
<P>
While exports will remain important, the domestic sector,
especially consumer spending, will be the dominant force in
Canada's economic performance, it noted.
</P>
<P>
At least 700,000 jobs will be created this year and next,
reducing the unemployment rate to an average of 8.7 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
While low interest rates will continue to provide stimulus to
interest-sensitive areas of the economy, short-term rates will
rise slightly, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The undervalued Canadian dollar will appreciate through the
rest of 1997 and 1998, even though it remains supportive of
Canadian exports, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
