<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Roosevelt Johnson, a key former
warlord in Liberia's civil war, today promised to cooperate with
President Charles Taylor in the country's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who fought Taylor bitterly only last year, was
appointed minister of rural development in the new cabinet of
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC, he said he will develop cordial
relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
"I think we all realized that there is no need to continue
destroying the lives and property of this country. I expect to
have a very cordial relationship with Mr. Taylor," said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing that makes him respect Taylor is his
promise that all Liberians will have equal opportunities and
there will be no witch-hunting and revenge.
</P>
<P>
"I respect him for that and I hope we all live together to
improve the nation," he added.
</P>
<P>
As for his new appointment, Johnson said, "We are not
interested in the job. We are eager to serve the people."
</P>
<P>
According to Johnson, the job as minister of rural development
is a challenge one especially when the country was destroyed in
the seven years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have to do something to prove to the people that
we are committed to the reconstruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Taylor named a 15-member cabinet last week. At least
three of his former rivals, including Johnson, are among the
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Although Taylor's government has been taking shape, many
observers are still watching how broad-based it will be. 
