<HEADLINE> Russia Favors Early Definition of Caspian Sea Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A legal status for the Caspian Sea
coordinated with all of the Caspian states could simplify the
solution of many problems, including the utilization of the
Caspian mineral resources, Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Valery Nesterushkin said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that most of problems around the Caspian Sea "are
caused by the absence of its legal status."
</P>
<P>
The Caspian theme is likely to figure prominently during talks
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Turkmen President
Saparmurat Niyazov in Moscow on August 7, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier, Turkmenistan expressed a resolute
protest against the production-sharing agreement on the Serdar
(Kyapaz) off-shore oil field, claimed by Turkmenistan, which was
signed by Russian oil companies LUKOIL and Rosneft, and the State
oil Company of the Azerbaijian Republic (SOCAR).
</P>
<P>
Niyazov told Russian Deputy Prime Minister Valery Serov in
Ashgabat at the end of July that his country would not conduct
talks on the status of the Caspian Sea until the Russian side
annulled the agreement on the development of this oil field
jointly with Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said Ashgabat does not hold any grudges against
Moscow "except in relation to this misunderstanding."
</P>
<P>
The Russian side assured Turkmenistan that Russian government
was not informed of the drafted agreement on Kyapaz, and said that
the document had been signed by Russian companies, not by
representatives of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The managers of these Russian oil companies have stated that
they will not take any steps in the Caspian Sea without
consultations with the Russian Foreign Ministry, Nesterushkin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
