<HEADLINE> Gebreselassie Retains Men's 10,000m World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia
unleashed a devastating surge one lap from home to win the men's
10,000 meters world title at the 6th World Athletics Championships
here today.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic and defending champion clocked 27 minutes 24.58
seconds, ahead of Paul Tergat of Kenya's 27:25.62 and Salah Hissou of
Morocco's 27:28.67.
</P>
<P>
Gebreselassie, who beat the 5,000m world record last month and
changed his mind in competing here, didn't plan to challenge his own
world record tonight. He just sat at second place and outkicked Tergat
easily for an expected win.
</P>
<P>
"This track has been a little better, not as hard as the one in
Atlanta. I am proud to have done a triple and I don't care anymore
about the world championships," the winner said after the race.
</P>
<P>
Gebreselassie had said that he wouldn't take part in the meet
because of the hard track. He beat the world 10,000 meters world
record last month.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian added:"If someone beats my world record I will start
to train again. I am not a person from another world, I am a human
being."
</P>
<P>
Tergat told the press:"I have the silver but it is never easy to
run in this sort of company. This is the first time for me at the
championships and so it is a great moment for me."
</P>
<P>
Hissou, Olympic bronze medal winner and the year's second fastest
time setter, promised at the press conference that he would attempt to
break the world record in Brussels on August 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
