<HEADLINE> Pro-Islamic Organization Raided by Turkish Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police today raided
offices and buildings of a pro-Islamic organization throughout the
country in search for fundamentalism-related evidence.
</P>
<P>
The raid was reportedly carried out under an order of the
Ankara-based State Security Court.
</P>
<P>
Police searched the headquarters and branches of the National
Youth Foundation (MGV) which is well-known for its affinity with
the pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP), according to Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Some videotapes recording speeches given by RP's former
outspoken parliamentary deputy Sevki Yilmaz were seized together
with a number of magazines in southern cities of Adana and Antalya.
</P>
<P>
In his speeches, Yilmaz attacked the eight-year compulsory
education reform bill proposed by the Education Ministry, which is
termed by the RP as a move directed against Islamic followers and
now is under a white hot debate in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The education reform bill has drawn strong opposition from the
RP and other conservative Islamists because of possible closure of
religious schools.
</P>
<P>
The police searched six MGV offices in the capital of Ankara,
but they declined to say if any criminal evidence had been found.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz
and his administration are now tightening grip on some
organizations having close relations with pro-Islamic RP led by
former prime minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military, which forced the June 18 resignation of the
Erbakan coalition government, and other secularists have always
been accusing the RP of conniving at the fundamentalist force in
the country. 
</P>
