<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Jamaican Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the completion of a 48 million
U.S. dollar syndication for a 72 megawatt barge-mounted power
plant--"Doctor Bird" near Kingston, Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
The plant is Jamaica's first independent power project and has
facilitated the development of a private power market. The project
sells its output to the national utility, Jamaica Public Services
Company (JPS). Fuel is supplied under a 21-year agreement by
Petrojam Limited, another Jamaican company. The plant began
commercial operations in October 1995, alleviating energy
shortages caused by the loss of capacity from a June 1994
explosion of two generating units owned by JPS.
</P>
<P>
IFC's total financing package is some 72 million dollars, which
consists of a loan for its own account of 22 million dollars, an
equity investment of 2 million dollars and a syndicated loan of 48
million dollars. The co-underwriters of the syndicated loan are
Merita Bank of Finland and ING Bank of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank and also the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
To date, IFC has invested about 900 million dollars equivalent
in 16 power projects in Latin America and the Caribbean, including
about 400 million dollars for IFC's own account and approximately
500 million dollars for the account of participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
