<HEADLINE> European Shares up, London Hits New Milestone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- All the three major stock markets
in Europe surged strongly and ended higher Wednesday, with London
hitting a new milestone, rising through the important 5,000-point
level.
</P>
<P>
Leading shares on the London market, Europe's largest, raced
ahead strongly today, with the FTSE 100 index storming to a new
record closing high, up 65.5 points at 5026.2.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that an unsettled opening on Wall Street failed to
dent London's enthusiasm, which was boosted by the pound's drop
and strong company results.
</P>
<P>
Sterling, which has kept on rallying recently, dropped four
pfennigs against the mark today and was also down to 1.60 US
dollars, a five-month low. This will benefit UK exporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, traders believed that the chances of rates rising
Thursday had receded because of complaints from exporters badly
hit by the pound's strength.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also made healthy gains although
activity was undermined by worries about a possible German
interest rate rise. The DAX-30 index ended up 32.71 points at
4,335.39, having shown little reaction to a larger than expected
rise in the July jobless total.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index closed 52.99 points higher at
3037.09, supported by strength in dollar stocks, notably oils, and
gains in financials.  
</P>
