<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Stresses Arab's Refusal of Unserious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri said here today that Arab countries will not agree to
hold "unserious" talks with Israel, and urged Washington to take
a "definite position" on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the remarks when talking on an upcoming shuttle
mission in the region of Dennis Ross, the U.S. special envoy to
the Middle East peace process, the official Lebanon News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab leaders have concluded that it is a loss of time to
hold talks which are only aimed at talks and which are not
serious," the prime minister stressed in an interview with an
Egyptian television, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government should take a definite position on the
necessity to continue (its mediation) until the end of its efforts
which should be based on the previously announced principles," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hariri attributed the current stalemate in the Arab-Israeli
negotiations to the intransigent stance of Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, saying that the Israeli government "does not
believe in peace."
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese prime minister accused Netanyahu's government of
attempting to abolish all agreements which Israel had signed with
the Arab sides, and all outcomes of negotiations which had been
achieved, and trying to force the Palestinians to accept
everything imposed by Israel on them.
</P>
<P>
"The negotiations should be resumed from where they had
stopped," Hariri underlined, "Israel should withdraw from the
occupied Lebanese and Syrian lands and implement the agreements
which have been signed."
</P>
<P>
In another interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency, the
Lebanese premier called for an Arab unity, noting that "the Arabs
can do a lot of things if they put their hands together."
</P>
<P>
"What we are now witnessing is because of a disintegration of
the Arab world from which Israel is benefiting," the Lebanese
leader said.
</P>
<P>
The interviews were made on the eve of a two-day official
visit to Lebanon by Egypt's Prime Minister Kamal Ahmed
El-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that he will hold talks with Ganzouri, who will
arrive in Beirut Thursday morning heading the Egyptian delegation
to meetings of the Lebanese-Egyptian Highest Common Council, on
cooperation and coordination between the two countries in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
Hariri reiterated Lebanon's support for the establishment of
an Arab common market, which was blueprinted by Egypt, but noted
that before this goal is achieved big efforts should be exerted
in order to overcome the difficulties. 
</P>
