<HEADLINE> Turkey's Chief Prosecutor Calls for Outlawing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief Prosecutor today
launched a new judicial initiative for the closure of the
pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP) led by former prime minister
Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
In his 80-page document submitted to the Constitutional
Court, Vural Savas, chief prosecutor of Court of Appeals, called
on the supreme judicial body again to outlaw the RP.
</P>
<P>
Describing the RP as a center force to connive at
fundamentalists, Savas said that this was an important step for
saving Turkey's democracy and secularism.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkey was facing a danger of the
resurrection of the rule of Shariah, or Islamic law, which would
challenge the country's secularist system.
</P>
<P>
The RP should hold responsibility for the rapid growth of the
fundamentalist force in the secular country, the chief prosecutor
added.
</P>
<P>
Savas filed his RP-closure case with the Constitutional Court
in May this year, triggering anger from the RP and its
followers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his RP parliamentary deputies Tuesday, Erbakan
threatened that he would call for judgement of the European
Court of Human Rights if his party is closed on grounds of
anti-secularism charge.
</P>
<P>
The RP had submitted a 215-page petition, containing its
preliminary defense, to the court, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to the legal procedure, the RP will have one month
to file its final defense with the Constitution Court. The party,
however, has reportedly applied for an extension of that period.
</P>
<P>
Once the RP prepares its final defense, the court will set a
date for both Savas and Erbakan to give their verbal statements.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military, with support of other secularist force,
forced the resignation of the Erbakan government on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and his RP have long been criticized for their
reluctance to take tough measures against the rapidly expanding
fundamentalists in the secular republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
