<HEADLINE> Greece Condemns Turkish-Northern Cyprus Pact on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Greece today strongly condemned an
agreement signed between Turkey and northern Cyprus which provides
for their partial integration.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
and northern Cyprus official Taner Etkin in Nicosia today, calls
for a Partnership Council to work towards the partial integration
on security, defense and foreign policy and full integration on
economy and finance.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that Turkey chose this particular moment to sign such
an agreement shows that despite its change in government it
insists in maintaining an internationally unique behavior towards
the world, disregarding laws and rules which it signs only to
transgress on them depending on its own interests," the Greek
Foreign Ministry said in a statement today.
</P>
<P>
The integration agreement came just a few days before the start
of a second round of U.N.-sponsored talks between Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
resolve the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The statement concluded that Greece would defend Cyprus'
freedom in cooperation with the Cyprus government on the basis of
U.N. resolutions and international law.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened it will unite with northern Cyprus if the
Cyprus government begins membership talks with the European Union
(EU). The EU has invited Cyprus to begin accession talks early
next year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro- Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a
breakaway state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which
has only been recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Currently, about 30,000 Turkish troops are stationed in
northern Cyprus to safeguard the security of the Turkish Cypriots
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
