<HEADLINE> UN Authorizes Mission in Central African Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The UN Security Council
today authorized the member states taking part in the
Inter-African Mission to Monitor the Implementation of the Bangui
Agreements (MISAB), and those states providing logistical support,
to ensure the security and freedom of movement of their personnel.
</P>
<P>
In resolution 1125 adopted unanimously today, the council
decided that the authorization is for an initial period of three
months. It was acting under Chapter VII of the UN Charter.
</P>
<P>
The MISAB was set up last January at the request of the Central
African Republic following some army rebellions. The mission of an
800-man force was deployed in Bangui on February 8.
</P>
<P>
At the Security Council meeting today, it had before it letters
from the presidents of the Central African Republic and of Gabon.
In the letter dated July 4, President Ange-Felix Patasse of the
Central African Republic requested for the Security Council to
provide a political and legal framework for the state members of
the Inter-African force by authorizing them to restore peace and
security in his country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the request is justified by the grave crisis in
his country stemming from the army rebellions, which left a large
supply of arms in the hands of former rebels and militiamen. He
persisted that tensions in his country could affect regional
stability and threaten international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
President Omar Bongo of Gabon also asked the council to
authorize the mission. The mission, under the political authority
of President Bongo, consists of troops from Burkina Faso, Chad,
Gabon, Mali Senegal and Togo while France will provide a
logistical command unit and financial support.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council asked the member states participating in
the MISAB to report to the UN secretary-general at least every two
weeks. After three months, the council will again assess the
situation on the basis of those reports.
</P>
<P>
Expressing welcome to the efforts of the member states
participating in the MISAB, the council approved the MISAB's
continued conduct of the operation in a neutral and impartial way
to facilitate the return to peace and security by monitoring
implementation of the Bangui Agreements. Those efforts include
supervising the surrender of arms by former mutineers, militias
and all others unlawfully bearing arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
