<HEADLINE> Russia Conducts Trial Overflight in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A team of Russian military experts
are in Canada this week to conduct a trial overflight under the
terms of the Open Skies Treaty, the Canadian government said
today.
</P>
<P>
The treaty between the countries of NATO and the former Warsaw
Pact allows the parties to conduct short-notice overflights of one
another's territory to collect information on military forces and
their deployment.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the treaty, Russia is entitled to photograph
anything it considers of military interest using only equipment
that cannot register objects of less than 30 cm across.
</P>
<P>
"This overflight is a new and encouraging dimension of the
ongoing cooperation between Canada and Russia in building
Euro-Atlantic security," said Canada's Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this signals that Russia will soon complete its
ratification of this important confidence-building mechanism," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Before the Canadian trials, the Russian team held similar
flights over the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
