<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Announces Smaller Deficit Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that the U.S. federal deficit in fiscal 1997 could be
as low as 37 billion dollars, smaller than expected and the lowest
in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton announced the latest forecast on the federal
deficit figures from his Office of Management and Budget at an
outdoor White House news conference. The current fiscal year will
end on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The new deficit projection for fiscal 1997 would be the lowest
federal deficit since 1974, when the government shortfall was 6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He also asserted that not only would the budget be balanced in
five year, but there would be a surplus of 20 billion dollars in
2002.
</P>
<P>
"These past months have been a remarkably fruitful time for
bipartisan actions in the national interest," Clinton said a day
after he signed bills to balance the federal budget in five years
and to provide the biggest tax cut since 1981.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit was as high as 290 billion dollars in
1992 and the deficit has been cut by a great margin in he past
four years after President Clinton took office in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gebreselassie and Sotomayor Chalk up Big Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- World record holders Haile
Gebreselassie of Ethiopia and Javier Sotomayor of Cuba claimed big
wins while Kenya's Moses Kipketer and Algeria's Noureddine Morceli
tarnished their names at the 6th World Athletics Championships here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The United States still lead the medal table with three golds,
three silvers and four bronzes, followed by Kenya, 2-2-1, and Germany,
2-0-2.
</P>
<P>
The day's other three golds were snatched by Hicham El Guerrouj of
Morocco in the men's 1,500m, Wilson Kipketer of Kenya in the men's
3,000m steeplechase and Tomas Dvorak of Czech Republic in the men's
decathlon.
</P>
<P>
Gebreselassie, defending champion and Olympic winner who improved
his own world record in the 25-lap event last month, played a
sit-and-kick game in the 10,000m final to win the world title three
times in a row in 27.24.58, yet well outside his world record.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian, who didn't want to compete in the meet because of
the hard track and joined in the force at the last minute, opened a
devastating kick 500 meters from home for an easy victory. Paul
Tergat of Kenya upset Olympic bronze medal winner Salah Hissou of
Morocco for the silver in 27:25.62.
</P>
<P>
"This track has been a little better, not as hard as the one in
Atlanta. If someone beats my world record, I will take it back. I
don't care anymore about the world championships," said a comfident
Gebreselassie.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor, who was narrowly beaten into second place at the
previous meet, dominated the high jump final completely, leaping over
a year's best of 2.37 meters, but gave up the tries after failing one
time at 2.41m.
</P>
<P>
Artur Partyka of Poland and Timothy Forsyth of Australia wound up
second and third, both at 2.35m.
</P>
<P>
The biggest upset today came in the men's 1,500 meters final, which
saw world record holder Morceli cruise home without a medal.
</P>
<P>
Guerrouj, silver medallist in 1995, kicked brilliantly to win the
title in 3:35.83, ahead of Spain's Fermin Cacho and Reyes Estevez,
both little-known in the world before the race.
</P>
<P>
"It was a classic example of a stay and kick race, with anybody
having his chance. My surge was fast and after it was just a matter of
controlling the pace, " said Guerrouj after his triumph.
</P>
<P>
Three Kenyans brought the packed crowd to their feet when Kipketer,
 Kiptanui and Bernard Barmasai made a clean sweep of the medals
in the men's 3,000m steeplechase final.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer burned up world record holder and three times world
champion Kiptanui on the home straight for a 8:05.84 win. Kiptanui,
who had planned to shatter the world record at the meet, led most of
the way but couldn't fend off the killing speed of Kipketer near the
finish. He was almost nipped by Barmasai at the line. They both
clocked 8:06.04.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight we surprised even ourselves. Kiptanui is still good, I
respect him a great deal. This is the first time I have run in the
championships and so I didn't believe it would won by me. The Kenyan
team is unbeatable at this event," exclaimed Kipketer.
</P>
<P>
The multi-event decathlon was won by Dvorak with a total of 8,837
points. Eduard Hamalainen of Finland collected 8,730 for the silver
ahead of Frank Busemann of Germany, 8,652. The hot favourite and the
world leader this year Chris Juffins of the United States had to pull
out of the battle after chalking up no marks in the ninth event -
javelin.
</P>
<P>
Dvorak, Olympic bronze medallist who improved his personal bests in
six events during the two-day fight, said:"During the whole
competition I was playing safe, never experimenting, just looking to
capitalize on my very focussed preparation for the meet. Six personal
bests in a decathlon like this is quite an achievement."
</P>
<P>
The day also saw Patrick Konchellah of Kenya, the third best in the
world this year, lost one of his shoe in the men's 800 meters heat.
The unlucky man said:"Losing my shoe right on the bell meant to run
without balance. Please find my shoe. I have got another pair but the
set I am running in today is the fastest."
</P>
<P>
So far after five days of competition, a total of 11 world
champions and Atlanta Olympic winners have either slumped out in the
qualifications or finished without a medal. Many new faces stormed
right at the occasion to achieve victories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
