<HEADLINE> Johannesburg the World's Cheapest City to Live </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest city
Johannesburg, also the industrial, economic and financial center,
has been rated out of the 145 countries worldwide as the cheapest
big city to live in, local press said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a twice-a-year survey by the Swiss-based
Corporate Resources Group, Johannesburg is the world's cheapest
big city with reference to the cost of a basket of more than 200
products and services including housing, food and alcohol,
utilities, clothing, transport and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
The survey, widely believed to be a snapshot of the relative
cost of living around the world, said Asia had taken up the
world's 10 most expensive cities, including China's Hong Kong,
Beijing, Shanghai and Tokyo of Japan.
</P>
<P>
It said Moscow of Russia kept its place as Europe's most
expensive city for the second year running, while the cities of
North America were rated among the most affordable to live.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Africa, the survey said Cairo of Egypt ranked as
the most expensive city in the continent, followed by Brazzaville
of Congo and Libreville of Gabon, while Harare of Zimbabwe was
Africa's second cheapest city after Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
However, Africa's highest climber in rating was Nairobi of
Kenya, which leapt 40 places from last year's survey to rank 75th
on this year's list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
