<HEADLINE> EU Forecasts Rise in Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Some two million new jobs will
be created in the European Union over the next two years as
economic growth picks up, the European Commission forecast today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest issue of The European Economy available today,
the executive body of the European Union (EU) forecast an EU-wide
growth rate of 2.4 percent this year as against 1.6 percent for
1996, driven mainly by export growth. The growth forecast for
1998 remains unchanged at 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Growth will also be helped by reduced inflation. Despite the
fact that 5.6 percent inflation in Greece pushed the EU's annual
inflation rate up slightly in June, average inflation is expected
to fall to 2.2 percent this year and to stay at that level for
1998.
</P>
<P>
The average deficit-to-GDP ratio in the EU is also expected to
fall from 4.3 percent in 1996 to 2.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Only two countries are forecast to have a ratio higher than the
3 percent limit set as a criteria for joining Economic and
Monetary Union in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among the other critera is a 60 percent debt to GDP ratio.
GDP. At present only four of the EU members qualify under this
criteria, the European Economy reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
