<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Climate Conference on Emissions Ends in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The week-long United Nations climate
conference on a new greenhouse gas emission accord concluded here
today, failing to agree on new targets and timetables for
emissions reduction by developed countries after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the seventh round of talks on new commitments by
developed countries to reduce their greenhouse gases after 2000.
Again, the rich nations shied away from any commitment.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan were largely blamed for the lack of
progress at the meeting, said conference sources. Neither of them
proposed anything, and the U.S. delegation said it would do the
same at the next negotiating session here scheduled for 20-31
October.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans are calling for reducing key greenhouse gases by
at least 7.5 percent from their 1990 levels by 2005. Earlier, some
rich countries had proposed a 15 percent reduction of emissions
from 1990 levels by 2010.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the conference today said that the
over 600 delegates from 145 nations were diverted from the central
question of precise targets and timetables during working on the
draft text of the new agreement under the UN Climate Change
Convention.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it quoted Ambassador Raul Estrada-Oyuela of
Argentina, the Chairman of the Ad hoc Group on the Berlin Mandate
(AGBM), as saying that various options were fully articulated and
clarified at the meeting, ready for governments to choose at the
October session.
</P>
<P>
Michael Zammit Cutajar, the Convention's Executive Secretary,
voiced concern in the press release about the slow progress at
this meeting. There is only a short time left to build necessary
political will for producing an effective agreement in Kyoto, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement is due to be finalized at the Kyoto
conference scheduled for 1-10 December.
</P>
<P>
The AGBM was established to negotiate new commitments by
developed countries to reduce emissions after 2000 and to promote
the implementation of existing commitments by both developed and
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
