<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Body Removed From Australia Landslide Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia's ski resort Thredbo
breathed a sign of sadness and relief today after the last body
was retrieved from the site of the landslide that devastated
Thredbo a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, rescue workers pulled the 18th body from
the ruins, accounting for all those believed to be sleeping in the
two lodges crushed in the disaster. The tiny ski resort is 150 km
southeast of Canberra, capital of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen people died in the tragedy. The only survivor was ski
instructor Stuart Diver, whose wife Sally today was formally named
among the dead.
</P>
<P>
"I think the feeling that you pick up around the village is
just one of relief that it is finally over," Thredbo Alpine
Village Managing Director David Osborn told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The massive rescue operation, which involved thousands of
police, ambulances, fire brigades and mines rescue staff and State
Emergency Service volunteers, was being scaled down today as snow
clouds loomed.
</P>
<P>
Asked about whether rescue workers had regrets about the
initial delay in the search of victims, Charlie Sanderson, the
police officer in charge of the rescue, said he and other rescue
workers had no regrets about the delay.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims were heard calling for help from beneath
the rubble just after the landslide late last Wednesday night, the
Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
But locals and tourists from neighboring lodges were forcibly
restrained from rescue attempts for fear of triggering more
landslides and killing any survivors, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
"At this point in time, there is no significant matter that I
can tell you that we would do differently," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The rescue on Saturday of Stuart Diver, suffering only minor
cuts and frostbite after 65 hours pinned between concrete slabs,
was a proof that the rescuers had taken the right approach,
Sanderson said.
</P>
<P>
The ski resort seems to have recovered from the week-long shock
as business in the village is starting to pick up, with numbers of
people skiing on Monday back to the same level as the day before
the disaster.
</P>
<P>
David Osborn said 2,500 people were on the slopes on Monday and
yesterday the number climbed to 3,000.
</P>
<P>
"People are ringing up, making bookings for later in the
season," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ski resort of around 300 people plans to turn the massive
landslide scar on the mountainside into a park with a memorial to
the 18 dead.
</P>
<P>
Snow clouds gathering over Thredbo lifted hopes of further
snowfalls to lure skiers back to the slopes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0087 </DOCNO>
