<HEADLINE> King Sihanouk Agrees to Appoint New First PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodom
Sihanouk today agreed to acting head of state Chea Sim signing a
decree appointing Foreign Minister Ung Huot as first prime
minister to replace Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Chea Sim, Sihanouk said, "I wish to express my
deepest thanks and wish to inform you about the request for a
decree to appoint a new first prime minister. If Your Excellency
thinks that it should be done, you can sign the decree."
</P>
<P>
Under Cambodian law, the appointment of a new first prime
minister would be illegal without a formal decree by the head of
state or his deputy.
</P>
<P>
Sihanouk said last month that he would not recognize Ung Huot,
who was nominated by Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party as his
replacement, as first prime minister because an election carried
out by an incomplete parliament would be illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot, who was supported by 86 of the 99 legislators present
in the National Assembly Wednesday to succeed Ranariddh, said this
afternoon that he, along with Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and
Chea Sim, would meet the king soon.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot, insisting his appointment was democratic and
credible, said the three-man group would seek the king's
support for the new government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
