<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Government to Monitor Hanson's Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The federal government was
determined to see controversial Independent MP Pauline Hanson "off
the stage," Acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer said today.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said the establishment of a special unit in the Foreign
Affairs and Trade Department to deal with Hanson's impact in Asia
was part of a wider response.
</P>
<P>
"It reflects a government getting on with the job of seeing
Hanson off the stage," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said that a small cross-divisional unit has
been established to monitor Hanson's impact in Asia and seek
opportunities to push the government's message that her views on
race are not typical of Australians.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that Australia enjoyed good relations with Asian
countries and the unit was part of "internal changes in government
to further fine tune the effort to deal with those elements who
would sabotage, divide and destroy these trading relations."
</P>
<P>
Bruce Baird, managing director of the Tourism Council of
Australia, said positive images of Australia, particularly in
Asia, were essential to the nation's continued growth.
</P>
<P>
"Although it is hard to quantify the effects that Hanson has
had on the tourism industry, recent figures show a decline in
growth in the number of Asian visitors to Australia," He said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Growth in visitors from Asia had fallen from 16 percent in the
1995-96 financial year to 5 percent in the 1996-97 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a fastest-growing industry in Australia and earned
more than 53 billion Australian dollars (40 billion U.S. dollars)
each year for the country, while the main source of visitors is
coming from Asia.
</P>
<P>
Hanson hit the headlines with her maiden speech to parliament
last September when she called for a halt to all immigration to
prevent Australia from being "swamped by Asians."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Suspends WTO Action Against US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union today
suspended its complaint against the United States at the World
Trade Organization after the U.S. agreed to change its rules on
textile imports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration formerly classified the origin of
finished textile products according to the source of the raw
materials. So, Italian scarves, German furnishings and British
cotton goods were classified as "Made in India" or "Made in China."
</P>
<P>
But the European Commission challenged these rules at the WTO
under a new instrument known as Trade Barriers Regulation, which
has been designed to improve market access for exporters.
</P>
<P>
The EC claimed the U.S. rules harmed top European designers and
manufacturers by undermining quality European labels as a selling
point among American consumers.
</P>
<P>
The EC also complained these products would come under quota
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
But after the U.S. agreed to modify the rules and guaranteed
that European exports would not be affected, the EC dropped the
complaint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Consolidate Economic Cooperation Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- In the year 2020, ASEAN will
gradually be consolidating and benefiting from the various
economic cooperation schemes launched two decades earlier,
president of ASEAN Chambers of Commerce and Industry (CCI)
Aburizal Bakrie said here today.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's economies will continue to grow in the next millennium,
although at a slower rate, with most member countries enjoying a
reasonable standard of living, Bakrie said at the press launch of
the "Private Sector Salute to ASEAN," which was organized by the
CCI.
</P>
<P>
He also said it is time for ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) to formulate an economic vision which will position
ASEAN well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN should build upon the prevailing peace in the region and
its expanded membership to enhance its global competitiveness so
that it will be able to compete successfully in a world of free
trade, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat of ASEAN and the CCI today also announced a
series of activities by the public sector to celebrate the 30th
anniversary of ASEAN's founding.
</P>
<P>
A private sector salute to ASEAN's anniversary will be held on
December 14-16 this year in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, as a major
event in conjunction with an informal summit of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Cambodia was
supposed to join the grouping, but its entry was delayed due to
the political turmoil in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
