<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Law on EEZ Put Into Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's 200-nautical-mile
exclusive economic zone (EEZ) went into force today, the Ministry
of Maritime Affairs and Fisheries said.
</P>
<P>
From today, the South Korean government will exercise its right
over resources and control foreign fishing operations in the zone,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
To protect its fishery resources and for safety, the government
also decided to delimit designated areas inside its territorial
waters, in which foreign vessels will be forbidden to conduct
fishing operations.
</P>
<P>
However, in a bid to publicize the new law, foreign fishing
vessels will still be permitted to enter its EEZ waters until
November 7, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese fishing vessels will be dealt with under the existing
South Korea-Japan Fisheries Agreement, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
In view of the talks between South Korea and China over a
fisheries agreement, Chinese fishing boats will be exempt from the
law until August 7, 1998, the ministry added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
