<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Space Shuttle Discovery Blasts off In Cape Canaveral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Discovery
with six astronauts blasted off today in Cape Canaveral, Florida,
on a mission to probe Earth's ozone layer and test a robotic arm
designed to perform meticulous chores on future space station.
</P>
<P>
The spaceship, with a total of 24 payloads including an
atmospheric-research satellite, rose into a hazy sky at 10:41
a.m. EST, right on time, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is supposed to spend nine days flying free of
Discovery, measuring atmospheric gases and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
During that time, NASA and the German space agency will launch
66 small rockets and weather balloons as well as a research plane
to examine the same piece of sky at the same moment as the
satellite.
</P>
<P>
Findings of the satellite will help scientists better
understand ozone depletion and develop more precise
meteorological models.
</P>
<P>
Among the six astronauts is Iceland's first astronaut, Bjarni
Tryggvason, who was born in Iceland and is now a Canadian citizen.
</P>
<P>
The crew will retrieve the satellite before returning home on
August 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
