<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Commemorates Sino-US Ping Pong Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Huang Hua, president of the China
Association for International Friendship Contacts, met with a US
table tennis delegation in Beijing's Great Hall of the People
today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is led by Rufford Harrison, former director of
the international department of the U.S. Table Tennis Association
and now chairman of the Equipment Committee of the International
Table Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
Huang, a former diplomat involved in the 1971 Sino-US Ping Pang
Diplomacy and later the foreign minister of China, said: "This
year is the 25th anniversary of the Ping Pang Diplomacy. It was
precisely this diplomacy that broke the ice in two decades of
estranged Sino-US relations and eventually led to the
normalization of bilateral ties and ensuing major changes in the
international situation."
</P>
<P>
Huang recounted past history by noting the hard-won Sino-U.S.
friendship. "We must take full advantage of new improved historic
circumstances to further promote the healthy and stable
advancement of the Sino-US ties," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu, Chinese minister in charge of State Physical Culture
and Sports Commission, attended the meeting. He noted that Ping
Pong Diplomacy was a great event in the history of the Sino-US
relations, as well as in the promotion of world peace and
development.
</P>
<P>
Wu expressed the hope that the peoples of the two countries,
athletes in particular, will continue to develop friendly
relations and strengthen cooperation and exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Harrison, who participated in related diplomatic endeavors 25
years ago, said that table tennis has contributed greatly to the
promotion of Sino-US relations, and he expressed the hope that the
sport would continue to do so in the future.
</P>
<P>
The current visit by the US delegation is part of the series of
activities commemorating the 25th anniversary of Ping Pong
Diplomacy. The China Table Tennis Association, the National
Committee on Sino-US Relations and US Table Tennis Association are
jointly sponsoring related activities.
</P>
<P>
Other activities include a recent US tour by a Chinese table
tennis delegation, and the International Men's Table Tennis
Masters Tournament which will open in Beijing tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the China Table Tennis Association hosted a
reception in honor of the US delegation and other foreign visitors
who will participate in tomorrow's tournament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CNAC, Dragonair To Build Office Towers at Chek Lop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Two aviation companies singed
an agreement with the Hong Kong Airport Authority (AA) here today
to construct a new office building at the new airport now under
construction at Chek Lap Lok, a reclaimed island west of Hong Kong
Island.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, China National Aviation Corporation
(Group) Limited (CNAC) and Hong Kong Dragon Airlines Limited
(Dragonair) will work together to build a complex with two
six-story office towers, involving a total investment of 1.4
billion HK dollars (180 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Scheduled to be completed in December, 1999, the building will
serve as a new headquarters and training facility for Dragonair
and offices for CNAC. The two firms will own the twin office
towers separately and share a common atrium, car park and
recreational facilities under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
AA's vice chairman Lo Chung-hing said at the signing ceremony
today: "This (the partnership) shows that all parties involved
recognize the importance of the new airport."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xian Lin, vice president of CNAC Group echoed Lo's
remarks, saying that: "Our investment in the building demonstrates
our confidence in Hong Kong's new airport as well as in the future
of Hong Kong's aviation industry."
</P>
<P>
He added that CNAC Group had already invested in aircraft
maintenance, air cargo terminal, fuel, flight kitchen and ground
handling services at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the new headquarters at Chek Lop Kok,
Dragonair, a regional airline based in Hong Kong, will for the
first time put all its operations ranging from pilot training to
management under one roof.
</P>
<P>
CNAC Group purchased around a 36 percent stake of Dragonair in
April, 1996 to become the largest shareholder of the airline,
whose Airbus fleet of 12 craft now flies to 25 destinations in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Chek Lap Kok new airport, one of the largest infrastructure
projects in the world, is slated to open its first runway in April
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
