<HEADLINE> Eight KAL Crash Survivors Flown to Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Eight injured survivors of
Wednesday's Korean Air Lines (KAL) crash in the Pacific island of
Guam will arrive in Seoul early Friday morning by a U.S. military
plane, the Central Accident Countermeasures Headquarters said
today.
</P>
<P>
A C-9 plane, equipped with medical facilities, has left the
Anderson Air Base in Agana, Guam, and is expected to arrive at
Seoul's Kimpo International Airport at 01:30 a.m. local time
Friday (1630 GMT Thursday), a spokesman for the headquarters said.
</P>
<P>
KAL originally planned to bring 18 survivors to Seoul in a
larger-sized DC-9 airplane early Thursday morning but later
changed its plan after consulting with U.S. military authorities.
</P>
<P>
KAL is planning to take to Seoul the remaining 15 South Korean
and four Korean-American survivors as soon as they have recovered
enough to endure the journey, he added.
</P>
<P>
The number of survivors of the crash was reduced to 27 after
three of the injured people died of severe burns early Thursday
morning. So far, 74 people have been confirmed dead and 153 remain
missing.
</P>
<P>
The KAL Boeing 747 flight with 231 passengers and 23 crew
aboard crashed into a forested hill near Guam's Agana
International Airport early Wednesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
