<HEADLINE> World's Astronomers to Meet in Hong Kong Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 experts from 15
countries and regions will meet in Hong Kong next week for an
astronomy conference, which can herald new opportunities for local
scientists, according to a press release of the Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology circulated here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first of its kind for Hong Kong, will be held
at the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology from August
13 to 16.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, named "1997 Pacific Rim Conference on
Stellar Astrophysics," these international experts will present
the latest research on supernovas, the sun, galaxies, white
dwarves, black holes, and the evolution of the universe.
</P>
<P>
The press release quoted Kwing Lam Chan, head of the
conference's organizing committee, as saying: "The research on
astronomy is not only an important pusher of space program, a key
measure of the level of technology, it is also important in
exiting people's interest in science."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the forthcoming meeting can catalyze
local science, technology, education and culture.
</P>
<P>
Among the leading astronomers attending the conference are
Riccardo Giacconi, former director of the Hubble Space Telescope
Program, and Li Qibin, president of the Chinese Astronomical
Society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
