<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Governor Urges Security Officers to Work Harder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira
has urged security officers and prosecutors to work harder to
maintain good security in the territory, the Macao Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The governor told the head of security forces and the chief
procurator that he was dissatisfied with their work and that they
should work more efficiently following a recent wave of
triad-related violence in the territory, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He urged them to eradicate "corrupt elements" in the forces and
improve procuratorial work so as to make a breakthrough in the
fight against crimes.
</P>
<P>
The report said the governor made these remarks on Tuesday
while meeting a group of representatives of the Macao Association
of Neighborhood Committee, one of the largest non-governmental
grassroots organizations in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The representatives expressed their concern at a sluggish
economy and a worsening security situation, saying it is the wish
of all residents that the government take effective measures to
boost economic growth and maintain a good social order.
</P>
<P>
The governor said he fully understood their concern and that he
 pays as much attention to the problems as they do. He stressed
that Macao's economy grew in 1997 although it is vulnerable to
outside factors.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined and also capable of boosting the
economy and maintaining security," he was quoted as saying. "All
residents should have confidence in the security forces and the
judiciary organs, and support their work."
</P>
<P>
Triad-related crimes over the past several months have marred
Macao's reputation, which in turn has hurt its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-year-long slowdown, Macao's economy has showed
signs of recovery since late last year. But it is believed to have
suffered a blow after tourist arrivals have dropped sharply in the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
Tourism and gambling income contribute to about half of the
revenue of the territory, which has an area of some 21 square
kilometers and a population of 420,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
