<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges to Help Mediate Abkhazia Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States will help
mediate in the conflict between Georgia and the breakaway region
of Abkhazia, Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff
chairman, John Shalikashvili, said in Tblisi today.
</P>
<P>
The United States supports the peaceful restoration of
Georgia's territorial integrity, the Interfax news agency quoted
the general as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia also plays an important role in mediating the conflict,
Shalikashvili told reporters at the airport after a three-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia, a rich Black Sea province, declared independence from
Georgia in July, 1992. Fighting began the following month when
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze sent troops into the region.
</P>
<P>
Separatists drove out the Georgian army in 1994 and agreed on a
ceasefire. Russian peacekeepers were deployed to prevent renewed
fighting between the two sides. But in spite of negotiations,
Abkhazia and Georgia have yet to find a formula to settle the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the Russian peacekeepers expired on July 31 this
year, but troops will stay on until a decision on their future is
taken at a summit of leaders of the Commonwealth of Independent
States in the fall.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations has decided to extend its unarmed
observer force in Georgia until January 31.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the U.S. general held talks with President
Shevardnadze and Defense Minister Vardiko Nadibaidze on military
cooperation between the two countries. Shalikashvili said the
U.S. will offer help in training Georgian military personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
