<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Coordinate Stances on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Jordan today called for
immediate actions to alleviate the escalating tensions between the
Palestinians and Israelis and salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh and his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa made the appeal at a joint press conference
following an enlarged Egyptian-Jordanian session of talks in
Egypt's northern port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh was accompanying Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan to
have arrived in the Mediterranean city earlier today for a
few-hour visit to Egypt following their talks with Israeli leaders
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Hassan conveyed a message from King Hussein of
Jordan to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged information about their recent contacts
with the Israeli government and the Palestinian National
Authority. Moussa said Tarawnh and he share the view that the
current situation is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
He urged Israel to lift its sanctions against the Palestinian
people following last week's double suicide bombings in Jewish
west Jerusalem which killed 13 Israelis and wounded 170 others.
</P>
<P>
"Theoretically or practically, the Israeli collective
punishment of the Palestinians are unacceptable," Moussa said,
adding that these measures would only aggravate the conditions.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept violence against innocent people, just as we
cannot accept the embargo against the Palestinian people," Moussa
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh noted that the grudges between the Palestinians and
Israelis go beyond the security issue. "They seriously differ over
the some political issues that have a direct bearing on the peace
talks," he added.
</P>
<P>
To deter the situation from going out of control,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's announced visit to
the Mideast by the end of this month would be most welcome, said
the Jordanian foregin minister.
</P>
<P>
Albright, when announcing earlier she would visit the Mideast
at the end of August, criticized activities that could aggravate
misunderstandings, without naming Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are reportedly working with the U.S. to
formulate an initiative which might be the basis for the
resumption of the stalled peace talks ahead of a visit by
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross to the region on the weekend
to defuse growing tension.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked since
Israel began the construction of a Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
After Israel decided to stop the plan of building another new
Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem, the two sides agreed to return
to the negotiating table on July 28.
</P>
<P>
But two days later, Israel immediately announced that it will
not resume the peace talks with the Palestinians after the deadly
Jerusalem double suicide bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
