<HEADLINE> Australia's Unemployment Rises In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Official figures released today
underlined continued weak jobs growth in Australia with the number
of unemployed people climbing in July.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said the official
unemployment rate rose by 0.2 percent to 8.7 in July compared to
8.5 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Financial market participants watched today's data carefully
for signs of weakness to hint at whether the Reserve Bank would
consider cutting interest rates further to speed up economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister Amanda Vanstone said in a statement that
"The (jobs) outlook for coming months is positive, however, with
the effects of the most recent interest rates cut yet to be felt".
</P>
<P>
"The economic fundamentals for sustained growth are extremely
positive, inflation is fully under control, the budget balance is
being restored and business investment is growing strongly," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
earlier this week, Treasurer Peter Costello also said
unemployment would fall to around eight percent by the end of the
current financial year ending June next year.  
</P>
