<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lanzhou Active in Reforming Housing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Lanzhou, capital city of
northwestern China's Gansu Province, is launching a comprehensive
housing system reform by gradually raising rent, selling
publicly-owned houses and establishing housing accumulation fund.
</P>
<P>
The city started housing system reform in 1993, later than
other regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
Housing rental fees, which were rising slightly every year
because of the less developed local economy and the residents' low
income, are expected to go up by 2.6 percent annually to reach the
final goal of 15 percent of a family's average income by the year
2000, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
The raising of rent for publicly-owned houses will effectively
alleviate the shortage of funds for house maintenance, and further
promote the socialization and commercialization of residential
housing.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 51 percent of the city's publicly-owned houses
have been sold to individual residents.
</P>
<P>
The city also made a breakthrough in raising housing
accumulation fund in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
