<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila's Visit Opens New Chapter in Angola-DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The first visit by President
Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to
Angola has been hailed as opening a new chapter in the history of
the relations between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos, Kabila paid a two-day visit to Angola from August 5-6,
his first visit to Angola since Kabila assumed presidency of the
DRC in May this year.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Angola, Kabila held discussions with dos
Santos and exchanged views on their domestic affairs, the
prospect of bilateral cooperation and international issues of
common interest.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents discussed situation in the African
continent, especially the political situation in central Africa.
They welcomed all efforts made by international community,
particularly the United Nations and the Organization of African
Unity to solve problems in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and dos Santos expressed their welcome to the newly
established African Economic Community, believing that it will
help promote Africa's development in the economic, scientific and
technological fields and push friendly contacts between African
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to step up cooperation between the two
countries to promote their prosperity, peace and sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed cooperation accords in the fields of
petroleum, mines, education, health, culture, transport and
fishery, which are bound to promote full development of bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Kabila's visit to Angola is a
successful one, which has ended the long-standing tension between
the two neighbors, arising mainly from the support by Former
Zaire's Mobutu government for the Angolan opposition UNITA (the
national union for the total independence of Angola ) in the
protracted Angolan civil war.
</P>
<P>
Just as a joint communique issued at the end of Kabila's visit
put it, the visit "opened a new chapter in the history of
relations between the two countries and their peoples".
</P>
<P>
The improved relations between them will promote stability in
the region and their economic development will also push the
regional economic development, observers concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
