<HEADLINE> Motorola to Increase Investment in Sichuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chengdu, August 7 (Xinhua) -- American electronics giant
Motorola plans to spend more than 200 million US dollars in
expanding a Sino-US semiconductor joint venture in southwest
China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Bill Miller, vice-chairman of Motorola's board of directors,
said recently in Chengdu, the capital city of the province, the
large investment in the third phase extension project of
Leshan-Pheonix Semiconductor Co. represents part of the company's
strategy to build the venture into China's semiconductor
production center.
</P>
<P>
First and second phase construction at Leshan-Pheonix,
Motorola's first joint venture in China, involved a total cost of
over 50 million US dollars, with some 95 percent of the venture's
output earmarked for export.
</P>
<P>
Third phase development will enable the venture to introduce a
new series of products, including power semiconductor devices and
integrated circuits. Most of the new products will be destined for
the export market.
</P>
<P>
Motorola plans to introduce state-of-the-art to ensure that the
joint venture maintains semiconductor production on a scale with
advanced world levels. 
</P>
