<HEADLINE> Security Stepped up in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Security at Uganda's Parliament
Building and most government institutions has been stepped up
following last week's grenade attacks in the capital, Kampala,
witnesses said here today.
</P>
<P>
At the National Assembly's main gate in the parliament
compound, policemen have since this week checked all visitors.
</P>
<P>
With exception of parliament members and journalists, bags of
all the visitors must be checked by the policemen at the
parliament gate.
</P>
<P>
At the gates of President's Office, ministries' compounds, the
same kind of check has been done by the policemen.
</P>
<P>
At the Crested Towers, where many important government
institutions are located, uniformed policemen have driven idlers
away these days and threat to arrest them if they are still
idling near the building.
</P>
<P>
Opposite to the Crested Towers, policemen at the Radio Uganda
checked every vehicle entering the compound this week.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 10 people were killed and 72 others injured by
grenade attacks in three deferent occasions im Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Two people have been arrested in connection with the attacks.
</P>
