<HEADLINE> UN Calls for Immediate Restoration of S. Leone's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council has urged Sierra Leone's military junta to renounce its
intention to remain in power and unconditionally restore the
elected civilian government it overthrew in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement released on Wednesday, the council
reiterated its "deep concern" over the developments in Sierra
Leone, noting that the crisis in the troubled country has
affected peace, security and stability of the west African
sub-region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed the necessity to abide by the agreement
reached between the junta's delegation and the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, last
month.
</P>
<P>
Describing the conditions proposed by the junta led by Johnny
Koroma for the restoration of the toppled civilian government as
"unacceptable", it called on the junta to resume peace talks with
ECOWAS immediately.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed welcome to the efforts of ECOWAS towards
resolving the Sierra Leonean crisis and support to the objectives
of ECOWAS' mediation initiative.
</P>
<P>
It demanded the junta immediately stop its threat by force on
Sierra Leoneans and foreign nationals in that country and do
nothing to disturb the international community's efforts to
provide humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Noting the influx of Sierra Leonean refugees into neighboring
countries, the statement called on all countries and
international organizations concerned to help these countries
settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
The talks between an ECOWAS committee and representatives of
the junta collapsed on July 31 following Koroma's announcement
that the junta would stay in power until a presidential election
is held at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping force of ECOWAS, known as ECOMOG, has
tightened economic sanctions and embargo against Sierra Leone at
the call of ECOWAS chairman, Nigeria's Head of State Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG statement warned on Wednesday that it would take
reprisal against any ship or aircraft attempting to enter the
territorial waters and airspace of Sierra Leone.  Endidtem

