<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Arab Delegation Leaves for Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A 48-member delegation of
Israeli Arabs left here this morning for Damascus in an attempt
to ease tension between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will hold talks with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad and other senior officials on the current Israeli-Syrian
relations, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Abed Inbitawi, spokesman for the Israel Arab leadership's
monitoring group, said that while the group wouldn't be relaying
any government-to-government message, "we hope we will have the
chance to help lessen the recent tension between the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
Inbitawi said a number of Israeli groups had asked to relay
messages, among them the United Kibbutz Movement which wants to
organize a meeting of Israeli and Syrian youths on the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
He said he had already looked into the possibility, but such a
meeting would be contingent on participants agreeing to a full
withdrawal from the Golan, as Syria has demanded in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Tourism Minister Moshe Katzav, who is also in charge of
Arab affairs, welcomed Wednesday the week-long mission, saying he
hoped it signaled the start of a new era for Israeli-Syrian
relations.
</P>
<P>
Katzav hoped that representatives would seek permission for
the widow and brother of Eli Cohen, who was executed in Damascus
on charges of spying for Israel 32 years ago, to visit Cohen's
grave.
</P>
<P>
Other delegation members included Labor Party member of
Kenesset (Parliament) Salah Tarif and Nawaf Massalha, as well as
United Arab List lawmakers Abdel Malik Dahamsha and Abdul Wahab
Darawshe.
</P>
<P>
The Hadash (Democratic Front for Peace and Equality) party and
Sons of the Village movement pulled out of the delegation over
political differences.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been deadlocked since
early last year, and showed no sign of resumption following the
rising to power of the current Likud government in Israel.
</P>
<P>
While Israel repeatedly called for resuming the talks without
any conditions, Syria demanded Israel's promise to withdraw from
whole Golan Heights before returning to the negotiating
table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
