<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The peace-keeping Operation Alba staged by 11 countries in
Albania was concluded on Wednesday as the last contingent of
French troops returned home from Albania. The result of this
operation was modest. Sixty people were killed last week in
Albania in lingering incidents of violence and the country is
still under the control of gangsters and mafias.
</P>
<P>
-- Situation remains tense in the Indian Ocean nation of the
Comoros as the chief of the separatists in the Comoran island of
Anjouan, Abdullah Ibrahim, chaired on Wednesday the first "cabinet
meeting." Meanwhile, the Comoran government has put its troops on
alert and has set up a crisis team to get in touch with the
separatists.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. dollar continued to rise on Wednesday and attained
6.37 francs and 1.885 German marks, registering a 22 percent rise in
exchange rates with the two European currencies since January. In
France as well as in Germany, exports, which serve as the motor of
economic growth, will benefit from a better competitiveness which
results from the rise of the green back. But it is bringing about
the rise of gas price in France and its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Fifty years after Jawaharlal Nehru declared independence of
India, the regional power which calls itself "the biggest
democracy in the world" is experiencing a 7 percent economic
growth, has the fourth largest armed forces in the world, has
attained self-sufficiency in food and is practicing a politically
alternative way. 
</P>
