<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Deficit Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China expects strong growth in
fiscal revenue and restrictions of expenditures to yield a 10
billion yuan deficit reduction in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to a recently released State Information Center
report, revenue are expected to account for a greater share of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Major factors contributing to solid growth in revenue income
include a significant increase in stamp revenue, improved taxation
measure, huge growth in tariff taxes, and increased income taxes
collected from profitable enterprises and individuals.
</P>
<P>
According to recent projections, state revenue will climb by 17
percent on a year-on-year basis, and in so doing will raised the
revenue to GDP proportion 0.4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, growth in budgeted expenditures will be held
at 14.7 percent annually as a result of reductions in state
government administrative spending and the cancellation or
postponement of construction of nonessential office buildings.
</P>
<P>
This year's low level inflation has helped to reduce state
subsidies and greatly reduced pressure on state spending.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beiersdorf to Buy 29.4 PC Stake in Poland's Cosmetics Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hamburg-based German chemicals
company Beiersdorf announced today that it would buy a 29.4 percent
stake in Poland's biggest cosmetics company, Pollena-Lechia SA.
</P>
<P>
Beiersdorf said that under a letter of intent, it would
eventually seek a majority stake in the Polish company as part of
its expansion strategy in Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
Beiersdorf will pay 50 million marks (26.4 million
U.S. dollars) for the 29.4 percent stake but a controlling
interest in the Polish company's business management.
</P>
<P>
Pollena-Lechia is based in Poznan and has an annual turnover of
about 60 million U.S. dollars. A 33 percent stake in the company
is held by the investment firm Fund Octava.  
</P>
</TEXT>
