<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian City Attracts More Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a coastal city in
Northeast China, has attracted more foreign investors than most of
the other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the city approved 360 foreign
investment projects, involving contractual foreign capital of
nearly 1.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far, Dalian has signed contracts with foreign investors to
establish 6,336 enterprises, involving a total of foreign fund of
11.8 billion dollars. As a result, the city ranks third, only
after Shanghai and Tianjin, in attracting foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Dalian takes some new ways of utilization of foreign
capital. State-owned enterprises attracted foreign capital by
issuing B share or transaction of property rights.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city has placed emphasis of attracting foreign
investment on boardering countries and regions. In the first half
of the year it sent delegations to Thailand, Indonesia, the
Republic of Korea (ROK) and Japan for business talks. In ROK
alone, the city signed 53 contracts on joint ventures, attracting
380 million dollars worth of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is working hard to improve its investment
environment. It has earnestly implemented relevant regulations and
held symposiums to solicit opinions from foreign investors. It has
also simplified procedures for the establishment of foreign-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By June this year, more than 3,000 foreign-funded enterprises
have gone into operation, accounting for about half of the
projects which have gained approval for the establishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advanced Buses Begin Service in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Starting from this Friday, Macao
will inaugurate ten Germany-made advanced public buses, which will
provide more comfortable and safer services than the previous ones.
</P>
<P>
The new buses, the first group of European tourism buses to be
used as public buses in the region, has cost the Transmac Bus
Company more than 10 million patacas (about 1.27 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 45-seat bus (10.3 m by 2.4 m by 3.16 m) reduces the steps
at the entry to only one, making it more convenient for children
and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
In addition, sensors have been installed at both gates of entry
and exit. Upon touching hard objects, the gate will open
automatically, and unless the exit door is fully closed, the bus
cannot be started, an engineer of the bus company said.
</P>
<P>
The newly-imported buses will be in service between the Hong
Kong-Macao Port Terminal and the Border Gate adjoining Zhuhai
City, south China's Guangdong Province, a leading route in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
Macao now has two public bus companies, with dozens of bus
lines. Buses remain the most convenient and most popular form of
transportation for local residents. The Transmac Bus Company now
has more than 300 vehicles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
