<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Ousted President in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah, ousted in the May 25 coup led by Major Johnny
Koroma, is in the Nigerian capital of Abuja for talks with
government officials.
</P>
<P>
There was no official confirmation of his visit up to last
night, but today's local paper, The Guardian, quoted sources as
saying that Kabbah, who has stayed in neighboring Guinea since
the coup, arrived early this week.
</P>
<P>
Altough the agenda of the talks is unknown, sources believe
that efforts to restore his presidency is the focus of
discussions.
</P>
<P>
Report of Kabbah's trip to Nigeria came together with actions
by the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to tighten
sanctions against Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG warned Wednesday that it would take reprisal against
any ship or aircraft attempting to challenge its blockade.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG warning, which became effective Wednesday, urged
all countries to impose "full sanctions and economic blockade
against the junta in Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations Security Council Wednesday
threatened unspecified sanctions against the troubled west
African country, which might lead to an arms and travel ban to
force the junta to relinquish power to Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which holds the chairmanship of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), has also initiated
moves to get the UN to impose full sanctions on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Security Council president Tuesday, Nigerian
Ambassador to the UN Alhaji Ibrahim Gambari formally brought to
the council's attention a policy statement made on the sanctions
by ECOWAS Chairman General Sani Abacha last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's announcement was made following the July 30 collapse
of the Abidjan talks between an ECOWAS committee and the junta's
delegtion.
</P>
<P>
"We want to inquire what the Security Council may now wish to
do, taking note of the ECOWAS chairman's policy statement,
particularly in reference to full-scale application of sanctions
and embargo," Gambari said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He also used the meeting to propose an amendment to the
council's draft presidential statement on Sierra Leone to reflect
the ECOWAS initiative.
</P>
<P>
If approved, the presidential statement will, among others,
blame the Koroma-led military government for the breakdown of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement, the third by the council since the coup, will
also call on the soldiers to withdraw their conditions for the
restoration of President Kabbah, renounce their declared
intention to remain in power and signal their readiness to resume
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Koroma has announced the junta will not hand over until a
presidential election is organized at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS foreign ministers have agreed to use a combination of
three measures to dislodge the soldiers -- dialogue, sanctions
and a possible use of force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
