<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korzeniowski Tops Men's 50km Walk in World Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Poland's Robert Korzeniowski, the 1996
Olympic champion, proved to be the toughest in the men's 50-kilometer
walk field when he returned home first to win the gold medal at the
6th World Athletics Championships here today.
</P>
<P>
He braved the hot sun to take the victory in three hours, 44
minutes 46 seconds. The heat (30 degrees) was the biggest obstacle for
all the walkers, but Korzeniowski didn't seem to be bothered and won
Poland's first gold at the meet.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Jesus Angel Garcia, the 1993 world champion and 1997 World
Cup winner, was second, 13 seconds behind the winner. Mexico's Miguel
Angel Rodriguez finished third in 3:48:30.
</P>
<P>
Korzeniowski and Carcia pulled away from Russia's Oleg Ishutkin
before reaching the 35th kilometer, and walked together in the next 10
kilometers. Korzeniowski made his decisive move and shaked off Garcia
after that for his first championships victory.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez caught Ishutkin in the final kilometers and maintained
his pace to the end.
</P>
<P>
The top three medallists walked the last 10 kilometers with two
warnings each, so they were very careful of not to make any more
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
Garcia was carried out of the stadium on a stretcher, but he only
had muscle cramps. After crossing the finish line he said that he had
never felt the heat like that.
</P>
<P>
The defending world champion Finland's Valentin Kononen, didn't
have a good day and only finished 9th. Five walkers including China's
Zhao Yongsheng, the 1993 World Cup winner, didn't finish the tough
race.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
