<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Spokesman on Turkey's Accord with Denktash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.-led direct talks aimed
at a Cyprus settlement should continue in spite of Turkey's
attempts to partially annex the Turkish-controlled northern
Cyprus, Government spokesman Manolis Christofides said here today.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on Wednesday's agreement on "partial
integration" between Ankara and the Turkish Cypriot regime on the
northern third of the east Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
and visiting Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, calls for
"gradual economic and financial integration and partial
integration on security, defense and foreign policy matters"
between Turkey and the self-styled "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Christofides told Cyprus radio that the signing of the
agreement was in line with Turkey's "routine political tactics of
creating problems," whenever hopes for a Cyprus solution are
looming.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "our European course is of vital importance
and we will take all necessary measures to safeguard it."
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government will make representations to
international fora about the accord.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that Turkey has a huge military
machine in Cyprus, and if it is concerned with Cyprus' military
buildup, "all it has to do is to accept President Clerides'
proposal for the demilitarization of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a breakaway
state in 1983 which was only recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
