<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Market Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sharply weaker performances by
market heavyweights BHP and Coca-Cola Amatil and a softer gold
sector drove the Australian share market lower today.
</P>
<P>
But the broader market held up well, buoyed by a 71.77 point
rise on the Dow Jones industrial average to 8259.31 overnight.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 9.4 points down at 2717.7,
having traded as high as 2738.2 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The market opened strongly but wasn't able to maintain its
early support levels with mining giant BHP, the largest company in
Australia, and Coca-Cola Amatil down and the gold stocks down,
Shaw Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
Shares in resources bellwether BHP sank 55 cents, or 3.06
percent, to 17.44 Australian dollars on a turnover of 7.6 million
shares, following yesterday's resignation of minerals division
head Dick Carter, and news of a review of the minerals division
following comprehensive overhauls at its three other main
divisions.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola Amatil ended 25.6 cents, or 1.56 percent, lower at
16.175 Australian dollars, off an intraday low of 15.90 Australian
dollars, with some analysts revising their full year forecasts
down on concerns over the company's European operations.
</P>
<P>
The gold index shed 16.9 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1279.8,
with gold bullion in Sydney trading at 318.85 US dollars an ounce
from 318.80 US dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 18.2 points down at 1418.6, with
Rio Tinto five cents firmer at 20.85 Australian dollars, Woodside
eight higher at 11.45 Australian dollars and WMC shedding two to
7.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index ended just 0.7 points lower at
4382.2, boosted by a 1.128 Australian dollar rise in Brambles
shares to 29.108 Australian dollars and a seven cent improvement
by Boral to 4.17 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 364.61 million shares valued at
928.39 million Australian dollars (687.01 million US dollars),
with falls beating rises by 571 to 528.  
</P>
</TEXT>
