<HEADLINE> Cyprus Takes Measures to Curb Road Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
determined to launch a massive road safety campaign to cut down
road deaths by half in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here today, Justice Minister Nicos
Koshis said with a population of merely 600,000, this eastern
Mediterranean island's road casualty rate is staggering.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents kill an average of 130 people each year in the
country, making Cyprus the second worst in Europe in terms of
accident fatality rate.
</P>
<P>
Between 1977 and 1997, a total of 2,100 people lost their
lives in road accidents in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Koshis believed that introducing tougher measures can save at
least 60 lives a year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that although road deaths are down by 30
percent for the first six months of this year compared to 1996,
there is more room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
Traffic policemen have been sent to Britain and Sweden to learn
about new techniques in road accident prevention, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the police showed around 100,000 out of
the island's 400,000 drivers are booked for traffic offenses
each year.
</P>
<P>
Until June this year, police had recorded over 60,000 traffic
offenses, nearly 8,000 more than in the same period in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garments Exports Up 10 Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Garments and textile exports
amounted to 1.72 billion U.S. dollars in the Philippines as of the
end of July this year, a 10 percent growth over the same period
last year, data from the country's Garments and Textile Export
Board showed today.
</P>
<P>
According to the data, increased demand from traditional
markets and continuing emergence of buyers from non-quota areas
pushed up the exports revenue.
</P>
<P>
Exports to quota countries accounted for 77.78 percent of the
total shipments with the income reaching 1.34 billion dollars. On
the other hand, shipments to non-quota areas went up by 8.8
percent as earnings rose to 382 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the biggest market among quota nations,
stepped up its purchases in the first seven months, garnering 62
percent of the total shipments. It was followed by European
countries and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Among non-quota countries, Japan was the biggest importers of
the Philippine garments, followed by the United Arab Emirates and
Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
