<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expert on Human Rights Dialogues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese human rights expert Fan
Guoxiang said here today that there are at least three subjects for
human rights dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Fan, one of the expert members in the Sub-Commission on
Prevention of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities under
the United Nations Human Rights Committee, made the remarks at the
sub-commission's 49th session. The current session meets between
August 4-29.
</P>
<P>
He said that in dialogues among those sharing the same view and
those holding different and even diametrically opposed ideas, at
least the following three subjects should be talked about:
</P>
<P>
- To exchange views and experiences for a better understanding
and to change an abnormal exercise of reaching conclusions prior
to talks. Well-organized attacks with a view to forcing political
country-wise resolutions run counter to the objective of promoting
human rights. Arbitrary accusations should be replaced by
strengthened cooperations.
</P>
<P>
- To seek common points. It is admirable to engage in
discussions on questions, for example, the universality and
specificity of human rights; the status, scope and focus of human
rights in the contemporary world as compared to their features in
various historical periods; ties between the economic, social and
cultural rights and the civil and political rights; birth and
development of conceptions and practices about human rights in
different regions and countries, and problems they are facing;
impacts on human rights by various historical background and
cultural heritage; relations between human rights on the one hand
and the maintenance of international peace and security and the
cooperation of the economic development on the other; individual
freedom and aggregate interest of the community; rights to be
enjoyed and duties to be fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
- To adopt a reasonable attitude toward divergences. One
should not be surprised by existing differences. The problem is
how to deal with them. Shouldn't we, on the basis of equality and
mutual respect, calmly explore the origin and scope of different
views? Are there any opportunities and conditions for any
progress, even partially and temporarily? If the answer is in the
affirmative, we are happy. If not, we can wait. Anyhow, this
approach will prove to be much more positive than an endless human
rights arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
Fan said that talks should be serious but not cosmetic, with
patience but not in a rush, in order to reach a gradual and
realistic common acknowledgment, either on substantive issues, or
on procedural matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Coffee Body to End Auction Monopoly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) --The Coffee Board of Kenya has
announced plans to introduce a multi-auctioneering system for
coffee in October and thus end the current auction monopoly, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The overall operations of the new auction system will be under
the Nairobi Coffee Exchange as an agent of the board, said the
board in a circular issued to planters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, the auctioneers will be required to
prepare a sales catalogue in liaison with the board and the
exchange on a first-in-first-out (FIFO) basis.
</P>
<P>
The auctioneers will also fix the reserve prices for their
clients. They will also negotiate fees and commissions which will
be deducted by the board and remitted directly to the
auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
The board also warned farmers not to sell coffee to companies
which are not licensed by the board.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, coffee futures prices soared above two U.S. Dollars
a pound for the first time in two months Tuesday on a report that
new Latin American supplies of mild Arabica beans could be months
late in arriving for roasters' use during the peak fall
consumption period.
</P>
<P>
Arabica coffee beans for September delivery rose nearly five
percent, or 9.35 cents, to 2.031 Dollars a pound, the highest
since June 17.
</P>
<P>
About 99.4 percent of Kenyan coffee is Arabica coffee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
