<HEADLINE> Southwest China Wax Printing Artist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Fuyuan, a specialist in wax
printing in China's Guizhou Province, has made a considerable
effort to develop the art form over the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Wax printing has a 1,000-year history, and Guizhou is the
hometown of the art form. Ethnic women there are skilled at it,
but most of their designs are simple and plain.
</P>
<P>
Hong, who is one of the country's top ten folk artists,
graduated from an ethnic minority art school in 1959 and was
determined to improve the art form.
</P>
<P>
After 37 years of hard work, he has designed more than 1,000
wax printing patterns in a variety of mediums, like pottery,
facial masks, grotto art, bronze decorations, stone paintings, and
ethnic artwork.
</P>
<P>
His designs have won many national prizes, and exhibitions on
his work have been held all over China.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture will send 32 of his wax prints to
international art exhibitions in Africa and North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
