<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Adventurer Crosses Lop Nur in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese explorer has walked
across the Lop Nur, the so called "zone of death" in China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, this summer alone.
</P>
<P>
Li Yongsheng, a 35-year-old adventurer, is the first man known
to have survived the dangerous walk across the massive desert in
summer.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the regional tourism bureau, Li
set out from Korla in the southern part of Xinjiang on May 18 and
took 40 days to complete the expedition.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures were above 60 degrees centigrade in June and Li
had to walk at night and rest during the day. On two extremely
difficult occasions, Li survived by drinking his own urine.
</P>
<P>
On another occasion when he was on the verge of death, he was
rescued by some people from an oil exploration team.
</P>
<P>
The Lop Nur once had oases on the legendary Silk Road, but the
sand began to cover it when the course of the Tarim River, which
had nurtured it, shifted. And the flourishing trade route began to
decline about 1,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1900s, a Swedish explorer discovered a
2,000-year-old city, Loulan, in the sand. And many archeologists
and amateur adventurers have been attracted by its mysteries,
ignoring its dangers. In 1981, Peng Jiamu, a noted scientist from
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, was reported missing in the
region and Yu Chunshun, 48, a well-known explorer, was found dead
in the desert in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Yu had ventured into the desert alone on June 12 and a gale hit
and the temperatures rose to 70 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Li Yongsheng, who is a graduate from the Central Academy of
Fine Arts, started a trek to visit all of China's 56 national
minorities in March 1989. Thus far, he has walked 94,000
kilometers and visited 30 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions. He also walked across the Taklimakan Desert, the "Sea of
Death," in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
During his 40 days trek on the Lop Nur, Li studied the desert
ecology and the ruins of Loulan, and took many lovely
photos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
