<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bavaria Continues to Support Ukraine's Medical System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bavaria will continue to aid Ukraine
in developing a sound medical care system, Bavarian State Minister
for Health Care Frau Stamm said today.
</P>
<P>
Stamm arrived in Kiev earlier today with medicine worth 450,000
deutsche marks (about 240,000 U.S. dollars) and a minibus for
disabled children in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Stamm, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Labor and Social Policies Mykon Beoblotsky praised
Bavaria as Ukraine's most generous donor.
</P>
<P>
Bavaria's aid to Ukraine over the past six years totaled 8.5
million marks (about 4.524 million dollars), about 60 percent of
which went for improving Ukraine's medical system.
</P>
<P>
Almost 100 Bavarian-Ukrainian joint medical projects are
underway in this east European country.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen company, in particular, built a medical center
in Ukraine for the rehabilitation of young people suffering from
nerve disorders at a cost of 2 million marks (about 1.1 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The center has been in operation since September 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
