<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening in China (III) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Active international economic exchanges also improved China's
foreign trade. The country's status among the world traders is up
from 15th in 1992 to 11th for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
China's trade went from 165.5 billion US dollars worth in 1992
to 289.9 billion dollars worth last year, a 75 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese products have established a reputation on
the international market. Last year, machinery and electronics
goods exports earned 48.2 billion dollars, 32 percent of the total
exports.
</P>
<P>
Certain other industries are also geared to the international
market. Ship builders have entered the Japanese and Korean
markets, the world's top two ship-building giants. The orders for
a number of China's leading ship-yards are reported to run to 1999
and into the next century.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is another economic index of the opening-up. China had
50 million overseas visitors last year, becoming the fifth largest
tourist destination worldwide, and earning 10 billion US dollars
from the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
