<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Municipality Seeks Balanced Growth in Urban, Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- With a heavily populated rural
area, Chongqing, which became China's fourth municipality early
this year, has been called "the largest village in China."
</P>
<P>
The city is located in southwest China on the upper reaches of
the Yangtze River. It covers 82,000 sq.km. and has a population of
30.2 million, 24 million of that in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The total rural population of China's other three
municipalities -- Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin -- is only half
that of Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
For more balanced growth, Chongqing is looking for a new
economic strategy to develop both urban and rural areas
simultaneously, and plans to quadruple the income of local
residents by the year 2010 from 1995's figure.
</P>
<P>
That means Chongqing will increase per capita income of urban
residents to 7,000 yuan from 4,643 yuan and that of rural people
to 2,350 yuan from 1,435 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing municipal government also plans to help 3.66
million poor people in rural areas live better by the end of this
century and to resettle one million residents of areas affected by
the giant Three Gorges Hydro-electric Power Project.
</P>
<P>
Lei Hengshun, a Chongqing University professor and government
advisor, says that the new economic strategy, called the
"Chongqing Model," has been worked out in keeping with the city's
special conditions and is important to China, with its large rural
population.
</P>
<P>
According to the municipality's Outline of the Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1996-2000) and the Long-Rang Objectives for Economic and
Social Development through the year 2010, it will build a
modernized city composed of towns of various sizes.
</P>
<P>
Liao Yuanhe, a local economist, says that the proposed city
will cover all 43 big and small towns in Chongqing Municipality
and form a large market for urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The new strategy will be helpful for spreading the use of
technology, information, and funds from urban areas to rural ones,
which have abundant resources for simultaneous and balanced
development.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Chongqing will further develop trade,
restaurant, tourism, and service sectors, and relocate a large
number of factories, mainly those in supplementary industries with
outmoded technology, to the countryside to help local township-
and village-based enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is one of six oldest industrial bases in the country,
and has many kinds of industries. To take advantage of this, it
will try to turn agriculture into a modern market-oriented
business by developing farm-based enterprises, agricultural
production bases, and individual farms in rural areas .
</P>
<P>
It will also improve its communications, telecommunications,
and information network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
