<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Reform Gains Momentum in North China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Shijiazhuang city in north
China has been successful with the housing reform, with handsome
returns from marketing commodity housing to be used for the
construction of more apartments.
</P>
<P>
For decades, urban residents in China used to live in public
housing with low rents, and they are now encouraged to purchase
their own apartments with the aim to step up housing construction
and meet the needs of the growing population.
</P>
<P>
After years of reform, things have changed greatly, especially
in 35 pilot housing reform cities, including Shijiazhuang city,
provincial capital of Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 16.04 million sq m of residential housing, 80
percent of the total in the city, built with state funds, have
been sold to individual families.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the city government has issued a series of
policies to encourage individual families to purchase their own
residential apartments, such as increasing rents and setting
reasonable housing prices affordable to local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
