<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Problem Threats National Security: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today warned that the illicit drug problem is considered a threat
to national security and, if left unchecked, could undermine the
political structure of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ramos painted this grim possibility during a dialogue with
members of the Foreign Correspondents Association of the
Philippines in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
"I'm warning the people about this (the drug menace to the
national security)," the President said as he called for everybody
to join the crusade to stamp out the drug problem once and for all
in the country.
</P>
<P>
To effectively address the problem, the government has
mobilized its entire machinery to fight an all-out war against the
illegal drugs that have hounded the country for so many years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos admitted that drug lords could, through their money,
maintain influence and connections in high places of business and
government in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, he vowed that the current anti-drug campaign would
focus on masterminds including the drug lords and their financiers
and that no let-up would be allowed in the drive.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he urged Congress to pass the
anti-racketeering bill that would give law enforcers the power to
freeze and confiscate laundered money owned by drug lords.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has become a key transshipment point by drug
lords because of its strategic position in Asia.
</P>
<P>
With over 7,100 islands scattered all over the vast archipelago
and its closeness to "the gold triangle" lying on the borders of
Thailand, Laos and Myanmar, it is easy to smuggle drugs into the
country, Ramos said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
