<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuzhou Promotes Cross-Strait Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Fuzhou, capital city of east
China's Fujian Province, has made it a point to promote trade
across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Security recently authorized Fuzhou to
issue Temperary Resident Cards for visiting Taiwan residents. The
move will facilitate inter-flows between the two sides of the
straits and help with cross-strait business transactions.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou, facing Taiwan across the straits, has one of the two
direct shipping lines between the two sides. And it only takes
half an hour to fly to the island from the city's Changle
International Airport, if direct flight is in operation.
</P>
<P>
Government support and geographical advantage have made Fuzhou
an ideal place for Taiwan investment. Some major Taiwan
enterprises like the Pacific Electric Wire and Cable Co. Ltd. have
set foot in Fuzhou.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 1,177 Taiwan-funded enterprises in Fuzhou,
involving a total investment of 2.93 billion US dollars. Another
2.62 billion US dollars can be expected in accordance with
agreements signed.
</P>
<P>
The investment covers the fields of textiles, shoe-making,
plastics, precision instruments, electronics, chemicals,
automobiles and motorcycles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Make Further Efforts To Reduce Automobile Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China will take further steps to
cut automobile pollution to improve the urban environment, says
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Bureau of Environment
Protection.
</P>
<P>
Since the country adopted the reform and opening-up policy in
the late 1970s, the number of automobiles has increased
rapidly. More than 50 percent of the air pollution in many big
cities comes from automobile exhaust.
</P>
<P>
Xie notes that the country will first take steps to deal with
fuel. China has been trying to stop the use of lead-containing gas
before the end of the century, and its gas production can meet
this goal.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin have decided to sell only
lead-free petrol by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The country will also inspect new automobiles and imported
cars. Those not meeting exhaust emission standards will be taken
off the market.
</P>
<P>
Old, run-down buses and trucks that cause serious pollution
will not be allowed on the streets, sources said, and other
automobiles will need exhaust emission controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
