<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birds Scenery in Summer Palace Drawing visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Summer Palace, located in
Beijing's western suburbs, has become a haven for birds, as well
as a popular tourist spot. It used to be China's largest imperial
park.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that half the bird species of northern China can be
found in the Summer Palace, and tourists can enjoy swans, wild
ducks, cuckoos, and orioles in the spring.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, a project to attract birds was launched on the
park's Longevity Hill. The bird lovers of Beijing put hundreds of
birdhouses in trees where birds could rest and breed, and a large
project for removing silt from Kunming Lake has turned it into an
ideal resting place for aquatic birds.
</P>
<P>
Three years of afforestation increased the moisture level,
providing a more suitable environment for birds to live in.
</P>
<P>
The unique scene of the birds has aroused tourists' interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
