<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Warns Britain over Visa Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will
appeal to the British government to waive the visa requirements
for Kenyans travelling to Britain, according to a "Kenya Times"
report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily paper quoted Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka
as saying at Parliament on Wednesday that the government might be
forced to reciprocate the visa requirement for British citizens
coming into the country.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the visa requirements imposed on Kenyans
were stringent and made it very difficult for Kenyans to travel
to the U.K.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Parliament that a Kenyan girl was
recently denied a visa to the U.K. where she was to marry her
fiance.
</P>
<P>
The girl was asked to return to the visa section for an
interview in April 1998 to determine whether or not she would be
issued with a visa, Musyoka added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government would consult with the British
government to relax the visa requirements, adding that if failed
in the talks, Kenya might be forced to impose the same rule on
British citizens.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that many of Parliament Members came out
strongly against the visa requirements imposed by the British
government on Kenyans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
