<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Easy Bail for Serious Offenders in S. Africa, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's cabinet has
approved a draft legislation, which will make it virtually
impossible for hardened criminals to obtain bail.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bail law, approved Wednesday, will force
experienced court officials to hear bail applications in murder,
rape and robbery cases, local daily, Sowetan, quoted Justice
Minister Dullah Omar as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, courts will refuse bail for suspects
previously convicted of a serious crime, except in unusual
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Besides, bail hearing outside normal court hours for
individuals accused of serious crimes would be banned.
</P>
<P>
"If properly applied, this bill is going to make a dramatic
impact on the hearing of bail applications," Omar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Criminal Procedure Amendment Bill would receive
priority and could be passed by parliament as soon as next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
