<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slowing Real Estate Sector's Use of Land in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The capital of Fujian province,
east China, has begun an endeavor to stop diverting land to
non-agricultural purposes, particularly to the real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
The move constitutes part of a nationwide drive to protect
arable land and check on the random use of farmland by real estate
businesses, according to officials from the city land
administration bureau.
</P>
<P>
Massive real estate development poses a major threat to
farmland in Fuzhou as well as elsewhere in China.
</P>
<P>
In its continuing check, Fuzhou has looked into 138 tracts of
land that were left idle by real estate developers and retrieved
33 tracts.
</P>
<P>
To cope with this situation, tough and strict measures,
including imposing fees on idle land and demolishing illegal
make-shift buildings, have been introduced in the city to protect
and save more farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Becomes Major Producer of Farm Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, in the subtropical zone in southwest China, has made
remarkable achievements in cultivating fine farm products in the
course of rural economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is viewed with importance in the country in the
production of sugar, fruits, silkworm cocoons, aquatic products,
meat and tea.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Governor Xu Bingsong told Xinhua that the autonomous
region, traditionally underdeveloped, injected great vitality to
the economic development through restructuring in the rural areas
which enjoy favorable natural conditions for farming.
</P>
<P>
Last year, rural industrial and service businesses generated
97.58 billion yuan in output value, or 52 percent of the total
gross domestic product in Guangxi's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Rural enterprises are growing fast. They scored 250 billion
yuan in business volume in 1996. The per-capita annual income for
farmers reached 1,703 yuan, above the national average.
</P>
<P>
As the country's no. one sugar producer, last year, Guangxi's
108 sugar refining mills turned out 2.36 million tons of sugar and
120,000 tons of alcohol, with a total economic return of 8.8
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is also a major fruit producer in China. Orchards in
the region have reached 937,000 ha., with an annual output of 2.4
million tons of subtropical fruits such as longan, litchi,
shaddock, mango, pineapple and banana.
</P>
<P>
The fruit processing industry is growing along with the
expanding fruit cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Due to fine weather conditions, Guangxi has good returns from
winter farming when most parts of the country suffer from cold
weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening-Up Drive (II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Investing in China came to be considered the development
opportunity for the coming century. China was the No.2 recipient
of overseas investment, after the United States, from 1992 on.
</P>
<P>
New characteristics in this appeared. Per-project investment
increased, for one thing. The average per-project investment has
increased from over one million US dollars to more than three
million dollars, and was as high as 30 million dollars in the
Suzhou Industrial Park, a Sino-Singaporean joint project in
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Source countries have also become more diverse. By June, 1997,
there had been investors from more than 170 countries and regions
in China.
</P>
<P>
Multinationals become more active. Of the world's 500 leading
corporations, 200 are operating in China.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment is now an important part of the Chinese
economy. The export volume of overseas-funded ventures in the past
five years had an average annual growth of 51 percent, and went
from 20.4 percent of the country's total exports in 1992 to 40.6
percent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
