<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Bombards South Lebanon in Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli artillery this morning
bombarded Iglim Al-Toffah, 60 kilometers southeast of capital
Beirut, in retaliation for pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerrillas'
attacks on Israeli positions in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment of Iglim Al-Toffah, a ridge often used by
Muslim militants as a springboard to attack the border strip
declared by the Israelis as "security zone," killed a woman and
destroyed several houses, security sources in the area said on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Hezbollah, or Party of God,
announced that its guerrillas fired salvos of Katyusha rockets and
mortar shells at the Israeli positions at Birkat Risha and Blat in
the western sector of the "security zone" Wednesday night. Some of
the rockets reportedly landed in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio claimed this morning that more than 10 Katyusha
rockets and mortar shells landed in the Galilee panhandle in
northern Israel without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
The escalation of tension came only hours before a five-nation
panel overseeing the implementation of a cease-fire agreement
between Israel and Lebanon meet at the south Lebanese border town
of Naqoura today at the request of both Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee will look into three
complaints filed by Lebanon and one by Israel.
</P>
<P>
In their complaints, Lebanon and Israel accused each other of
violating the cease-fire understanding the two countries reached
in April, 1996 which bars the fighting sides in south Lebanon from
targeting civilians.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee comprising representatives of France,
Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States have held 15 meetings
since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by Muslim guerrillas and retaliatory
bombardments by the Israeli forces constitute a daily scene in
south Lebanon, making the area the last active battlefront of
Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 15-kilometer-wide strip in south Lebanon
along the Israeli-Lebanese border, with a total area of up to
1,100 square kilometers, as a "security zone" in 1985 to buffer
northern Israel from cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
