<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Import 550,000 Metric Tons of Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines would have to
import some 550,000 metric tons of sugar if it continues exporting
to the United States, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sugar Regulatory Administrator Wilson Gamboa told a press
conference that he prefers to stop all exports of sugar to the
United States despite rejection by the Presidential Palace and the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his recent visit to the United States, he
again explained his proposal to "voluntarily give up the U.S.
quota" even if it would mean losing the U.S. market to other
supplying countries.
</P>
<P>
"We'll sacrifice a lot in terms of national integrity if we
continue supplying the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that until the sugar supply situation is stabilized,
his country could not look beyond the domestic problems and
supplant U.S. sugar requirement.
</P>
<P>
Meeting the U.S. sugar quota allocation would mean a higher
price of sugar in the domestic market, thus rendering the
Philippine sugar uncompetitive in the world market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the quota, the country should export 250,000 metric tons
of sugar, or 15 percent of the national sugar production, to the
United States this year, Gamboa said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
