<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Hits S. Africa Worst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The cases of the most
common cancers in South Africa, cancer of the oesophagus,
prostate, stomach, cervix and breast, are among the highest in
the world, according to an academic report.
</P>
<P>
About 23,000 deaths a year for the next 40 years will be due
to lung cancer from cigarette smoking, and the number of
Aids-related cancers is also expected to rise significantly, a
local daily The Star today quoted the annual National Cancer
Registry (NCR) report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the South African Institute for
Medical Research Wednesday, showed that, based on 1992 figures,
one in 39 black men have a lifetime risk of developing
oesophageal cancer.
</P>
<P>
Cancer of prostate is most common in white (one in 20) and
colored (one in 30) men, and cancer of the stomach is the most
common in Asian men (one in 64).
</P>
<P>
Among women, cancer of the cervix is most common in black (one
in 26) and colored (one in 30) women, and breast cancer is most
common among white (one in 15) and Asian (one in 20) women.
</P>
<P>
These figures are drawn from the 51,517 cases reported via a
countrywide network of private and public pathology laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The NCR warned that the South African government must tackle
cancer if it hopes to sustain health advances so far achieved,
for example, by increasing control of communicable diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
