<HEADLINE> Egyptian Prime Minister Arrives in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri arrived here this morning on a two-day official visit
to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri landed at the Beirut International Airport at 10:10
a.m. (0710 GMT) and was received by his Lebanese counterpart Rafik
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
The two will hold talks at the Beirut Governmental Palace in
the morning, which will be followed by a meeting this afternoon
between Ganzouri and Lebanese President Elias Hrawi.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Ganzouri and Hariri will preside over
meetings of the Lebanese-Egyptian Highest Joint Council.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Middle East News Agency today,
the Lebanese prime minister said that he will discuss with his
Egyptian counterpart coordination between the two countries in the
economic and trade fields and the establishment of an Arab common
market.
</P>
<P>
"We support free trade between Lebanon and Egypt but we have
to study it in detail to achieve the greatest benefits for both
countries," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he would like to encourage Egyptian companies to
participate in Lebanon's reconstruction projects "because of their
wide experience in reconstruction and because of their
competitive prices."
</P>
<P>
The billionaire-turned prime minister is the architect of
Lebanon's ambitious reconstruction programs.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Lebanon's exports to Egypt were valued at 16.8 million
U.S. dollars while its imports from that country totaled 54.6
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Egypt ranked 11th on the list of Lebanon's most important
trade partners in 1996, according to statistics of Lebanon's
customs. 
</P>
