<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Split over Planned Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Nationwide strike set for Friday
has split Kenya's opposition ranks, as two key opposition leaders
say no to the strike which is planned by opposition's umbrella
body National Convention Executive Committee (NCEC).
</P>
<P>
Opposition FORD-Asili Chairman Kenneth Matiba said Wednesday
that he is opposed to the mass action's timing, a day after
FORD-Kenya leader Kijana Wamalwa announced the same stance, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 30 opposition members of parliament and several
other opposition leaders said they fully supported the strike
call aimed to speed up the constitutional reform process, adding
all arrangements are in place to make sure it is a success.
</P>
<P>
A strike Friday would inconvenience Muslims greatly and would
also be impractical since the NCEC and the church had just
presented their seven resolutions on political reforms to the
president for approvement.
</P>
<P>
The strike should be suspended because President Daniel arap
Moi has instituted dialogue with interested parties, Wamalwa
stressed in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the door to peaceful and non-violent resolution of
constitutional issues remains open, all mass action such as the
threatened strike must be suspended," said FORD-Kenya
Secretary-General Gitobu Imanyara Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition lawmakers, led by Democratic Party
chief Mwai Kibaki, have urged "all workers, matatu (mini-bus)
operators, and business people to cooperate to make the Nane Nane
(August 8) strike a resounding success."
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers demanded that the government shelves the
Constitutional Review Commission Bill and the Statute Law Bill
until they are discussed between NCEC and the government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenyan Labor Minister Philip Masinde declared illegal
the strike Sunday, warning that the government would not protect
workers who may lose their jobs as a result of participating in
the strike.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here Sunday, 10 Kenyan trade unions
accused the NCEC of hijacking the labor movement in the country
by calling for a strike.
</P>
<P>
The trade unions called on workers, leaders and the labor
movement to shun the strike and warned the NCEC to stop inciting
workers against their employers and the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
