<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PCCI Opposes Tax on Foreign Currency Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Chamber of Commerce
and Industry (PCCI) expressed its strong opposition today to a
proposed legislative measure imposing taxation on foreign currency
deposits in commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
PCCI President Federico Pascual said that if the bill is
enacted into law, many of the country's depositors will have no
choice but to pull out their dollar deposits and transfer them to
other tax-free places.
</P>
<P>
At present, the total foreign currency deposits in various
banks in the country are estimated at 17 billion U.S. dollars.
They helped a lot to sustain the country's economic growth,
Pascual said.
</P>
<P>
If passed, the bill will defeat the country's economic
objective of attracting more dollar depositors and stunt the
growth of the banking industry because depositors will be
discouraged to put their foreign currencies in the local banks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that this move is counter-productive to the
government, saying the change of the ground rule will directly
affect the economic objectives of the government at this time when
the country is slowly recovering from the July 11 currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to Pascual, the proposed law would directly affect
the import and export sectors, the manufacturing industry and
those who source raw materials from abroad or who are paid in
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
