<HEADLINE> Half Million S. African Children Unable to Go to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than half a million
South African children of school-going age are not attending
schools, local press Sowetan reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figure was based on the October Household Survey of 1995
Statistical Service, the newspaper quoted Education Minister
Sibusiso Bengu as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that there was a severe shortage and poor
condition of facilities, basic provisions like water,
electricity, toilets, telephones and extremely high classroom
shortages.
</P>
<P>
Early on Tuesday, Bengu confirmed that most schools in the
country were either in bad conditions, or in need of facilities.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a quarter of the country's schools had no water within
walking distance, less than half of schools had electricity, and
many schools experienced a shortage of toilets, he quoted a
register of education institutions as saying. 
</P>
