<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Produced from Waste in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
developed a new method to burn urban waste and produce heat for
electricity generation or heating.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Yan Jianhua, one of the leaders of the project, said that
some 40 researchers from the Thermal Engineering Institute of
Zhejiang University, got involved in the development.
</P>
<P>
According to Yan, the waste was put into a container to be
burned at a temperature of 800-900 degrees centigrade. "The size
of the waste can be reduced 90 percent after burning and the
closed container can prevent smoke pollution," said Yan.
</P>
<P>
People usually think that waste treatment was only an
environment-friendly activity with no economic returns. "The
concept is wrong," Yan said. "Waste treatment can be profitable."
</P>
<P>
The facility has been put in use in a thermal power plant in
east China's Shandong province. Last year alone, it treated more
than 60,000 tons of industrial waste and produced four million kwh
of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Also in June last year, a burning stove with a daily treatment
capacity of 65 tons of industrial waste was exported to the
Republic of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
