<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 07:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Objects Foreign Military Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's new President Mohammad
Khatami has made a veiled call for the withdrawal of U.S. troops
from the Persian Gulf, according to a report here today.
</P>
<P>
"All the regional countries have to cooperate with each other
and build a secure and thriving region without the presence of
foreigners," he said at a meeting with Oman's special envoy
Mohamed al-Rawas on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In analysis, the new president said if the interests of foreign
powers coincided with those of the regional countries, then there
was no reason for their physical presence in the area because the
regional countries could defend their own rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
"If the foreign powers' interests were against (those of) ours,
then they should not be allowed to continue their presence in the
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States now has about 30,000 troops with heavy
military facilities in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Tehran sees the massive U.S. military presence as a major
threat to its national security, especially after Washington
threatened to take retaliatory measures if Iran is found
implicated in terrorist activities against American interests.
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami did state during his oath-taking ceremony
Monday that Tehran wants to have relations with all countries. In
so saying, he did not exclude the U.S. and Israel, as his
predecessor Hashemi Rafsanjani used to.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Omani envoy delivered a message from
Sultan Qaboos in which he extended congratulations to Khatami and
stressed the need to further strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said "the fact that Iran and Oman are located at the
two ends of the strategic Hormuz Strait is of great significance,"
adding security and tranquility were the two basic criteria for
construction and development.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Iran is extending a hand of friendship and
brotherhood to all countries especially those in the region
seeking friendly relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that cooperation as well as exchange of
ideas with regional states would prepare proper grounds for
better and more effective ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
