<HEADLINE> Statistics: Israeli Life Expectancy Among World's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli men enjoy one of the
highest life expectancy in the world, according to a report of The
Jerusalem Post today, quoting an announcement of the country's
Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS).
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy in 1995 reached 79.5 among women and 75.5 in
men. Among Jews, those figures rise to 79.8 and 75.9
respectively. Since 1993, the life expectancies for both women and
men have increased by 0.4 years.
</P>
<P>
More than half of all females born between 1991 and 1995 will
live to be older than 81, with 50 percent of the males passing
78, predicted the CBS Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest world figures available for comparison showed that
in 1993, Israeli men were ranked third highest in the longevity
table at 75.5, slightly behind the Swedes. Japanese men live the
longest, an average 76.5. U.S. men had a life expectancy of 72.2.
</P>
<P>
Israeli women were in 17th position, averaging 79.1 years. In
comparison, Swedish women live to 82.3, Japanese to 83.1, and
Americans to 78.8.
</P>
<P>
Of Israelis born between 1991 and 1995, some 20 percent of
girls and 10 percent of boys will live to become
nonagenarians. Men who reached pension age between 1991 and 1995
can expect to live for an average of 15.6 years in retirement,
with 65-year-old women likely to live another 18 years.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli population by the end of 1996 totals 5,763,200 and
80.8 percent are Jews. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
