<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Ballerina Part Of Beijing Ballet Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian ballerina Nina
Ananiashvili held center stage last night in Beijing's Exhibition
Center Theater, as 2,700 people watched her execute her jetes as
she flourished a fan.
</P>
<P>
Ananiashvili's exuberant portrayal of Kitri in "Don Quixote"
was the climax of an international ballet star program of Russian
and Swedish ballet dancers who had never performed in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The classical ballet pieces included "Pas de Quatre",
"Giselle", "Nutcracker", "The Sleeping Beauty", "Raymonda",
"Carnival in Venice" and "Don Quixote Grand Divertissement".
</P>
<P>
Beijing's ballet enthusiasts crowded outside the theater
looking for a chance to gain admission ticket, some still hanging
around after the performance had started.
</P>
<P>
Ten ballet dancers were the most popular, and there were
prolonged cheers and long bursts of applause by Chinese ballet
lovers.
</P>
<P>
China Performing Arts Agency (CPAA), the organizer, said that
the city has never been treated to an exceptionally grand
performance like this one.
</P>
<P>
"I never imagined that a Chinese audience would understand
ballet so much. It's my greatest pleasure to make people happy,"
siad the 34-year-old ballerina, who is regarded the most
outstanding and successful combination of acting and dancing.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Ruheng, director of the National Ballet Troupe of China,
said the performance represents the highest standard of ballet
today. "We saw the unadulterated and exacting Russian classical
heritage. It's passionate, dramatic and exciting," the Chinese
ballerina who has co-operated with famous foreign ballet dancers
and companies, said.
</P>
<P>
She said she hopes China's ballet, which has a history of only
38 years, will study the elite materials from world-known ballet
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
