<HEADLINE> 3.5 Million Poor People Benefit From World Bank Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- About 3.5 million people in
southwest China's Yunnan and Guizhou provinces and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region have benefited from aid-the-poor projects
involving the World Bank assistance.
</P>
<P>
A total of 200 million US dollars in low-interest World Bank
loans are funding aid-the-poor projects in 35 counties covering
education, public health, agriculture, infrastructure
construction, labor service and rural industrial development.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, Guizhou and Guangxi are among China's underdeveloped
regions with an annual per capita income of 300 yuan (about 37 US
dollars) for the farmers. The country's rural average is about
1,900 yuan (230 dollars).
</P>
<P>
To implement the World Bank aided projects, the central
government asked the regions involved to provide necessary
supporting funds.
</P>
<P>
Among them, education and public health projects are most
successful.
</P>
<P>
In 10 poor counties in Yunnan province, 76,000 poor children
have completed primary school studies and 2,133 primary school
teachers have received training, and more than 70,000 square
meters of school buildings were put up.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan also built 25,000 square meters of rural clinics and
trained 1,300 health workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
