<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Implement Compulsory Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to implement compulsory education before long after
reports that 10 percent of the country's children are not
attending school, according to the Education Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that although the literacy rate in Sri Lanka
has been put at 84 percent, recent reports show that it is not the
case in some community groups.
</P>
<P>
As a first step to enforce compulsory education in the country,
the ministry will conduct a countrywide research on children who
are not attending school.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, approximately 10 percent of
school-age children do not enter any school.
</P>
<P>
Measures will be taken to help these children enter schools or
non-formal educational institutions, the ministry said.  
</P>
