<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Emerges as Most Cohesive Regional Grouping: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) has overcome its initial gloomy picture to
emerge as one of the most cohesive regional groupings in the
world, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad says.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
published today in conjunction with the 30th anniversary of
ASEAN's founding tomorrow, Mahathir said ASEAN leaders had been
able to pull through despite early difficulties and make a success
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
"I must admit that when ASEAN was first formed, I was not too
hopeful that it would succeed. There were too many differences
between the parties to the agreement. It would not be possible for
them to cooperate but I must say I was wrong," he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN was set up on August 8, 1967 when five founding members
-- Malaysia, Indonesia, Philippines, Singapore and Thailand --
signed the Bangkok Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The regional grouping now comprises nine members with Brunei
Darussalam joining in 1984, Vietnam in 1995 and Myanmar and Laos
in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that when ASEAN was formed, it was basically to
help resolve problems between neighbors.
</P>
<P>
There was some kind of tension, but ASEAN provided a forum to
resolve the problems, if not fully, at least to reduce the
tension, he said.
</P>
<P>
The member countries opened up their economy to foreign
investors and this resulted in economic growth and subsequent
prosperity, he said, adding that with the transfer of technology,
ASEAN countries themselves became able to participate in
industrialization.
</P>
<P>
"So I would say that over the 30 years, the initial gloomy
picture has been overcome and ASEAN has emerged as one of the most
cohesive groupings in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
On his fears for the region, Mahathir said ASEAN need to be
wary of efforts by outside parties to dominate their economy.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving into the so-called information age and
borderless world. We have to open up our economy (but) our own
companies and corporations are not yet strong enough to compete
with those coming from outside. There is a real danger of our
economy being totally dominated by foreign companies with huge
sums of money and greater technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the only way for ASEAN to react was to act together.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir does not rule out the possibility of a multi-media
convergence being forged among ASEAN countries in the future with
Malaysia pushing its Multi-media Super Corridor (MSC) project,
Singapore its Information Technology program and the Philippines
its own cyber scheme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Suffers Setback in Insurance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Front government
suffered a major embarrassment in the Lok Sabha (lower house of
parliament) on Wednesday when it was forced to withdraw a
controversial bill on insurance reform at the time of voting, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision to withdraw the bill, designed to open India's
insurance market to foreign firms, was taken when the government
encountered stiff resistance from the opposition Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) and other parties to the entry of multinational
companies into the insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral and Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram tried unsuccessfully to ward off this embarrassment as
they sought to defer the voting on the bill by appealing for more
time for further consultations.
</P>
<P>
The government gave in to the persistent demand for the
withdrawal of the bill when it became clear that a BJP-sponsored
amendment barring the entry of foreign companies would be passed
with the support of not only its allies but also the left parties,
which are constituents of the ruling 13-party United Front.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party, which supports the Gujral government from
outside, decided to abstain from the voting on the insurance
reform bill.
</P>
<P>
Though it declared opposition to the BJP amendment, it was
unable to muster sufficient numbers as most of its members had
left for the party's forthcoming plenary session scheduled for
August 8-9 in Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament supporting the BJP-amendment clearly
outnumbered those opposing it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
