<HEADLINE> Indian Minister Calls for Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram has appealed for more efforts towards environmental
protection because it goes hand in hand with economic growth, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on environmental preservation, the
minister quoted a study as saying that environmental degradation
is costing 10 percent of India's national income.
</P>
<P>
Environmental costs of natural resources should be included in
the pricing of products like water and power, he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about environmental protection, Chidambaram said India
has the technology to arrest, prevent and reverse environmental
degradation, but lacks the ability to mobilize social and
political forces to set relevant initiatives in motion.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a tendency to put too much reliance on the
government in checking environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The government should involve itself at three levels -- as
policy framers, regulators and punishing authority for violators
of law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Beyond that, the involvement of community-level organizations
alone can safeguard the country's environment, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
