<HEADLINE> NZ Minister Sacked by Party Boss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sacked Associate Health
Minister Neil Kirton said this afternoon he had also quit his job
as Customer Minister, deepening a crisis within the New Zealand
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Kirton, a list MP from the New Zealand First party, was sacked
this morning as associate health minister by his party leader
Winston Peters, who is deputy prime minister in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Kirton had been at odds with Health Minister Bill English, who
is from the National Party.
</P>
<P>
Peters told the press that Kirton had ignored his instruction
to make no comment about the dispute with English, but Kirton went
on radio this morning in disregard to the clear instruction.
</P>
<P>
However, Kirton said at a press conference this afternoon that
no such instruction was given and he was sacked because of his
opposition to greater privatization of the health system.
</P>
<P>
He said he would remain an MP and would consider his future
with his NZ First,
</P>
<P>
At an emergency meeting after Peters dumped Kirton, the NZ
First caucus unanimously supported the decision made by Peters.
</P>
<P>
Under the coalition agreement, NZ First will name another MP to
fill the post left by Kirton, and any minister could only be
dismissed by the leader of his own party.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that if Kirton departs with NZ First, the
coalition will be in real trouble as the two partners, National
and NZ First, enjoy only a one-seat majority in the 120-member
parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
