<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five U.N. Peacekeepers Died in Helicopter Crash in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Five members of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) were killed when their helicopter
crashed last nignt in an Israeli-occupied border strip in south
Lebanon, the Daily Star reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash, which took place late last night
near Bint Jbeil, 120 kilometers south of the Lebanese capital,
was not immediately known but appeared to be accidental, the Beirut
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter, an Italian air force Bell Augusta and one
of the five used by the south Lebanon-based U.N. peacekeeping
forces, was on its routine flight checking on UNIFIL positions
when it crashed in a valley between the villages of At-Tiri
and Rshaf.
</P>
<P>
It crashed just 800 meters west of At-Tiri on its way returning
to the UNIFIL headquarters at Naqoura, a UNIFIL source said,
adding that before the incident, the helicopter had landed briefly
at the Irish battalion's post in the village.
</P>
<P>
All five people on board were killed, the source said. The
pilot and co-pilot were Italians and one passenger was identified
as an Irish UNIFIL serviceman but the remaining victims'
nationalities have not been checked out.
</P>
<P>
The crash site was in an area heavily patrolled by
Israeli troops and their client the South Lebanon Army militia
and located between three SLA positions.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army immediately declared a state of emergency in
the so-called "security zone", which the Jewish state established
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The five casualties brought to 214 the number of UNIFIL
personnel who have died in south Lebanon since the nine-nation
peacekeeping forces were first sent to the area in May,
1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Small Industries Urged to Form Linkages with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today called on small and medium scale industries
(SMIs) in ASEAN countries to form inter-firm linkages with their
larger counterparts to ensure the strengthening of the
industrialization base of the economy.
</P>
<P>
These linkages are important in ensuring the strengthening of
the industrialization base of the economy and providing market
access and the opportunities for cross-border transfer of
technology, he said when opening the ASEAN-East Asian Business
Forum here.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike some East Asian countries like Japan and Korea, the
SMIs in most ASEAN countries are still weak in terms of
inter-linkages with larger counterparts," he noted, saying it was
therefore their task to learn from these countries and try to
adopt and adapt the strategies to suit the requirement of each
country.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said in the new millennium, SMIs must assume a greater
and more important role in enhancing and strengthening the economy
of ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) and the East
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that the SMIs must not only concentrate on
building up entrepreneurial expertise but must be competitive and
must be prepared to undertake changes to survive the competition
and respond flexibly to market needs.
</P>
<P>
The competitiveness of SMIs could no longer rely on cost
efficiency alone. Equally important was the ability to offer
products, services with higher quality and greater value added, at
internationally competitive prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SMIs must adopt a global perspective of manufacturing and
marketing, invest in the right type of technology and processes
for efficient production and undertake research and development to
develop and improve products to gain significant market share, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is for the entrepreneurs themselves to use their
creativity and innovative strategies to build up their market
niches, both domestically and globally, rather than just depending
on government assistance and facilities to spearhead their
development."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said it was envisaged that in a decade, ASEAN would
emerge as a unified Southeast Asia sharing common goals and
economic vision in making the region a boon to investors and
businesses alike.
</P>
<P>
Adjustments need to be made in the way investors and firms
operate in the region and under the new trade and industrial
environment, they must look ASEAN as one larger market and not
just relocating themselves just to serve one particular ASEAN
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
A major challenge to ASEAN would be to keep international trade
open, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN presently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
