<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Takes Urgent Steps To Curb Sea Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Fisheries and
Aquatic Resources Development Ministry has taken urgent steps to
control sea erosion, which has rendered hundreds of residents
along the coastal areas of the south homeless.
</P>
<P>
Minister Mahinda Rajapakse has asked the authorities of the
Coast Conservation Department (CCD) to expedite their work day and
night in bringing the situation under control, according to the
Ministry sources today.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 35.5 million rupees (610,000 US dollars) has been
allocated by the government for the purpose, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They said both permanent and temporary measures will be taken
against sea erosion in south of the country.
</P>
<P>
The CCD has already put up sand pillows along the Lunawa
coastal line as a temporary measure and will commence work on
building a permanent stone buffer at a cost of 100,000 US dollars,
the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
