<HEADLINE> Dhaka Makes Fresh Bid to Persuade Return of Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government today
sent a seven-member delegation to the neighboring Indian state of
Tripura in a fresh bid to persuade some 40,000 tribal refugees
there to return.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by lawmaker Ranjan Chakma, is expected to
visit different camps in southern Tripura and meet leaders of the
Chakma refugees, who fled their hometown in a brush war going on
between the armed forces and the pro-independent armed tribal
rebels since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 refugees were repatriated in two groups in 1994
while 7,000 others returned between March 28 and April 7 this
year after the peace talks made progress between the new
government and the tribal rebels.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation process, however, was halted as the refugees
claimed that Dhaka had not fully complied with its commitments,
under which the refugees should be provided with cash, food
rations, cattle, building materials and jobs.
</P>
<P>
After that, the refugee leaders in India declared that the
remaining refugees will not return home unless their repatriation
and resettlement are supervised by international bodies.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka, however, rejected the demand, arguing that the Indian
authorities did not allow international agencies to look after the
refugees in Tripura.
</P>
<P>
As the stalemate in the repatriation process cast a long shadow
on an expected peace accord on the decades-old tribal rebel
problem, the government decided to send the delegation to Tripura
to sort out the issues once again with the refugees and their
hosts.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, scheduled for a three-day visit, is to return
home on August 9.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
