<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Bans Some Drugs, Bottled Water for Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar health authorities has
banned some 14 brands of traditional drugs and 26 local and
foreign brands of purified bottled water for public consumption in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Official paper The New Light of Myanmar today quoted the Health
Ministry's announcement as saying that the listed brands of drugs
and bottled water are unfit for use for the public.
</P>
<P>
The designated 14 brands of traditional drugs, manufactured and
distributed in the country, were found not purely traditional ones
but processed with western medicines as ingredients and deemed
dangerous after undergoing tests, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the authorities also discovered that 26 brands of
purified bottled water on sale in the country do not meet
prescribed micro-organic and chemical standards after
examinations.
</P>
<P>
Of the 26 brands of bottled water, Iceberg and Ranong are
imported, the announcement pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The paper, in its editorial, called for examination of all soft
drinks, locally bottled or imported, to ensure safety for public
consumption, reminding the public to beware of bogus medicines and
drinks which can harm people's health.  
</P>
</TEXT>
