<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Foreign Debt Said to Reach Alarming Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's total foreign debt
has reached an alarming level and should be addressed before the
economic condition becomes worse, a prominent economist here
noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a one-day seminar held by Citibank here Wednesday,
Sjahrir said Indonesia's total foreign debt is expected to reach
120.5 billion U.S. dollars by the end of this year with 34.3
billion dollars in short-term loans, accounting for about 28.5
percent of the total foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt in the country has increased continually in recent
years, amounting to 116.5 billion dollars in 1995 and 118 billion
dollars in 1996, Sjahrir, managing director of the Institute for
Economic and Financial Research, was quoted as saying by the local
press today.
</P>
<P>
He told the seminar that the increasing foreign debt was
related to the ballooning private sector debt. "There is an
indication that the private sector has a serious problem in paying
back its foreign debt. This must motivate all of us to avoid the
worst financial crisis, such as what occurred in Mexico."
</P>
<P>
Sjahrir said the country's current account deficit is
escalating. He estimated that the current account deficit in the
1998/99 period would reach 10.6 billion dollars, an increase of
800 million dollars from the estimated 9.8
billion dollars for this year.
</P>
<P>
"The current account deficit escalated because the export
growth slowed down while the import growth remained high," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Export is expected to grow about 12.5 percent and import 13.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The total export value is estimated to reach 53.9 billion
dollars in 1997, compared with 61.9 billion dollars for imports.
</P>
<P>
Sjahrir said that if the country can register an economic
growth of 7.7 percent this year, it will see a better performance
of 7.8 percent in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0253 </DOCNO>
