<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czechs Kill More on the Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents claimed a total
of 615 lives in the Czech Republic during the first half of this
year, a 10 percent increase in victims compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Czech traffic police bureau said that
drivers and pedestrians separately accounted for one third and a
quarter of those killed in the 93,000 traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of cars per capita in the Czech Republic is
obviously lower than western European countries, the fatality rate
is much higher.
</P>
<P>
Czech fatalities in traffic accident per million population are
150, double the rate of Scandinavian countries.
</P>
<P>
A major cause for the high death rate was non-compliance with
traffic rules, such as driving after drinking alcohol, driving
against red lights and excessive speeding, a report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
