<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wilkins To Start Second Season in Magic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Guard and forward Gerald
Wilkins resigned with the Orlando Magic Wednesday to start his
second season with the National Basketball Association club.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Wilkins averaged 10.6 points, 2.2 assists and
2.2 rebounds in 80 games last season, including 26 starts. He
scored in double figures 44 times with a season-high 25 points
against Dallas December 2.
</P>
<P>
The veteran has averaged 13.8 points, 3.2 assists and 3.1
boards over 825 career games with New York, Cleveland, Vancouver
and Orlando in his 12-year NBA career.
</P>
<P>
Orlando had previously re-signed forward Derek Strong and
forward-center Amal McCaskill. Guard Nick Anderson and center
Danny Schayes remain free agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Appropriate Money for Expanding NATO Air Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government will provide
near 1 trillion lira (about 550 million U.S. dollars) for a
project to expand a U.S. and NATO air base in Aviano, a city in
northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
The whole project includes the construction of more houses for
accommodation of U.S. servicemen and their dependents, shopping
facilities and other service facilities in the air base, local
press reports quoted a senior government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Defense Ministry also will allocate money for the
expansion project, he added.
</P>
<P>
The number of troops stationed in the air base will rise to
3,000 by the end of this century from 1,700 at present, the
official said, adding that the Aviano air base will then become
the largest U.S. and NATO air base in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, some local officials have been worried about the
planned project, while local residents also have launched peaceful
protests outside the air base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand Seek to Reduce Narcotic-Drug Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Drug control officials of Myanmar
and Thailand are meeting here to seek ways of reducing the use of
narcotic drugs and controlling HIV/AIDS in the Myanmar-Thai border
areas.
</P>
<P>
A two-day meeting, which began Wednesday, is being held between
a Myanmar delegation and a visiting Thai delegation under the
Myanmar-Thai joint narcotic drug control program, according to
today's official daily The New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The two delegations exchanged views on plans, strategies and
joint operations in implementing anti-drug projects in the
Kengtung and Tachilek areas in Myanmar and the Chiang Mai and
Maesai areas in Thailand, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Delegates of the Bangkok-based Economic and Social Commission
for Asia and the Pacific and the U.N. Drug Control Program (UNDCP)
also gave suggestions at the meeting, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand signed a drug control cooperation
agreement with the UNDCP in June 1992 and had implemented, between
1994 and the end of 1996, integrated and rural development, law
enforcement and demand reduction in Myanmar's Tachilek, Ahdee and
Hsanlu areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
