<HEADLINE> U.S. Security Advisor Prepares for Jiang Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States National
Security Advisor, Sandy Berger, will fly to China this weekend to
prepare the groundwork for a visit to Washington this fall by
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, the White House announced today.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman Anne Luzzatto said Berger would depart for Beijing
Saturday and stay in China until August 13.
</P>
<P>
The trip was "a continuation of the high-level strategic
dialogue begun last year," she said. Its main goal was to discuss
preparations for Jiang's state visit to the United States planned
for late October.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs
Stanley O. Roth, and National Security Senior Director for Asian
Affairs Sandra J. Kristoff, will join Berger on his four-day
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
