<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italians Restrict Nighttime Airport Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Ministry of Environment
issued a decree today partially banning aircraft takeoffs and
landings at domestic airports at night, in an effort to curb noise
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, at all the airports except the
inter-continental airports in Rome, Milan and Bergamo, planes will
not be allowed to take off and land between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m.
The exceptions will include planes operating medical care,
emergency rescue and postal services.
</P>
<P>
As a component of anti-noise pollution package measures, it
aims at decreasing the noise nuisance for residents around the
airports.
</P>
<P>
The decree forces 16 airports to change time tables, and will
be put into operation next June 30.
</P>
<P>
Because of the increasing development of air transport, planes
generating noise levels lower than 60 decibels will not be
effected by the new decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
