<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Eases Shandong Drought Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River in Shandong
Province, which has been dry for 132 days, received water from its
upper reaches yesterday morning, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The water, which flowed into the Bohai Gulf last night, is
expected to help ease the drought in western Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Kong Guofeng, an official with the Shandong Yellow River
Administration, said water flowed through the Lijin Hydrometric
Station at 510 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, the main water source of western and northern
Shandong Province, dried up in Shandong and other provinces in
February after drought struck its upper and middle reaches.
Shangdong Province also experienced the worst drought in decades
this year.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the local water conservancy department said the
precipitation will relieve the serious drought in southern
Shandong Province, but the drought in northwestern Shandong and
Jiaodong Peninsula is still severe.
</P>
<P>
More than 3.7 million hectares of farmland are suffering from
drought, and the direct economic loss is expected to reach more
than six billion yuan (722 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the last 25 years, the river has dried up 19 times. Experts
warned that the dry spells are longer each year.
</P>
<P>
The dry spells have cost industries and agriculture along the
Yellow River 26.8 billion yuan (3.2 billion US dollars) in the
past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The dry spells have also damaged the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Palestinians to Resume Cooperation With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
urged here today the Palestinians to resume their security
cooperation with the Israeli authorities as tension builds up in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians should act on the information they have and
"if there are people there who are real serious threats to the
peace and to innocent civilians, they should be kept behind bars
if it is legal to do so," Clinton told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"The people that murdered all those people, those innocent
civilians, are not trying to get a peace that they think is more
favorable to the Palestinians," the president added.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a duel bomb attack last week which killed
15 people and wounded more than 150 others in Jerusalem. The
suicide bombing has led to the Israeli closure of the self-ruled
Palestinian areas and the arrest of dozens of Hamas activists by
either the Palestinian Authority (PA) or Israel.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also urged Israel to take "a responsibility to try to
carry its end of the load," stressing "This has get to be a
two-way street."
</P>
<P>
He said he would send his special mediator Dennis Ross back to
the troubled region this weekend to talk to PA President Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu mainly on
security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
here today that she is planning to travel to the Middle East by
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
In a luncheon speech, Albright urged both the Palestinians and
Israelis to do more to advance the peace process, which, she said,
had been set back for six months by a "crisis of confidence."
</P>
<P>
She asked the Palestinians to do more to contain terrorists,
while calling on the Israelis to refrain from undertaking
"unilateral acts" that erode Palestinian confidence.
</P>
<P>
Washington is not content with the Israeli construction of
Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem but reluctant to force it to
stop.
</P>
<P>
Press reports speculate that Ross and Albright may bring about
some new ideas to put the peace process back on track, but little
has been spelled out so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
