<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emission Standards for Cement Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- All cement plants in China will
be required to government emission standards within the next three
years or will face forced closure.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Bureau, State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC), and State Bureau of Building Materials Industry has
introduced the measures to accelerate the standardization of dust
emission.
</P>
<P>
China's cement industry accounts for well over 60 percent of
the nation's annual six million tons of highly polluting dust
emissions.
</P>
<P>
Small township enterprises account for near 80 percent of
China's cement plants.
</P>
<P>
The SETC plans to eliminate the use of obsolete technology, and
is preparing to list acceptable new technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela's Exports Rise in First Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's non-traditional
exports hit 2.19 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of 1997, a
20.6 percent rise over the same period last year, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured products and goods grew 53.3 percent to 463
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the U.S. increased 11.1 percent, to Colombia 2.7
percent, to Japan 78.2 percent, to Mexico 79.6 percent, to Ecuador
24.2 percent, to Brazil 71.4 percent and to Peru 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The most important non-traditional exports include common
metals, chemical products, food, tobacco, beverages, minerals and
electrical materials.
</P>
<P>
Private companies generated 74.7 percent of the total exports
(1.71 billion dollars) while State-owned enterprises accounted for
25.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
