<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Footballers End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Professional footballers
ended the two-week long strike from July 22 on Wednesday, when the
Argentine Football Federation (AFF) and a television station paid
up to secure the release of six players.
</P>
<P>
The six Deportivo Espanol players had announced their release
from their club, but the club said the six were part of its assets
despite expiration of contracts.
</P>
<P>
Eventually the AFF stepped in to promise that players could
move as soon as their contracts expired after the dispute had
prompted to a strike.
</P>
<P>
The striking players had refused an earlier appeal by President
Carlos Menem and mediation attempts by veteran star Diego
Maradona, who is currently making his fifth comeback to Boca
Junior.
</P>
<P>
The last three games of the season had to be squeezed into a
10-day period. Officials said that "it was vital to resume playing
as quickly as possible." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
