<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian government has set up a special policy unit
to fight negative images generated in Asia by the rise of Pauline
Hanson. The unit will target the Asian press and news wire
services and try to publicize the government's position on
immigration and Aboriginal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australia has to overcome intellectual, political and
economic obstacles to end the "national disgrace" of unemployment,
Kevin Manning, chair of the Australian Catholic Social Justice
Council, said yesterday. He condemned the government's
"inactivity" in the jobs crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard is expected to return to work on
Monday after an absence of three weeks because of pneumonia, but
he will not be able to slip quietly back into office. He is
scheduled to chair a cabinet meeting before flying to Queensland
to campaign for mid-term election.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Retail investors pumped almost 1.8 billion Australian
dollars (1.35 billion U.S. dollars) into equity funds in the 12
months up to June 30, more than four times the amount in the
previous year. The rush of new money came as investors chased the
strong returns generated by the buoyant sharemarket.  
</P>
</TEXT>
