<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, China Satisfied with Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Both China and Pakistan are
satisfied that their time-tested relationship has remained vibrant
and strong as ever in spite of new developments in the regional
and global scenario.
</P>
<P>
This was jointly expressed here today by visiting Chinese Vice
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad during their talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks covered bilateral relations, economic collaboration,
cooperation in international fora, regional situation and other
matters of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
During the talks Tang said that relations between China and
Pakistan are "all weather ties."
</P>
<P>
Shamshad recalled that China had extended assistance to
Pakistan at critical junctures and contributed significantly
towards its goal of economic self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
China's participation in major economic projects and in the
development of various sectors of Pakistan's economy has been
invaluable, he said.
</P>
<P>
On regional issues, Shamshad said that Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif had initiated resumption of dialogues with India to
find a peaceful solution to the core issue of Kashmir and to make
progress on other outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also expressed satisfaction on the close cooperation
at the United Nations and other international and regional
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Tang, who arrived on Monday evening for a two-day visit to
Pakistan, left here for Colombo, Sri Lanka, later this evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak-China Relations Is A Model of Inter-State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari said here today that relations between his country and
China have become a model of inter-state relations worthy of envy
and emulation by others.
</P>
<P>
Leghari made the remarks when he met visiting Chinese Vice
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan who arrived here Monday evening for
a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting the president appreciated the positive and
useful contributions China has made in the economic development of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his confidence that special relations between
the two countries would be further deepened.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he emphasized the need for further expansion in
bilateral trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Tang Jiaxuan conveyed to Leghari the good wishes of Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Prime Minister Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Tang also expressed the confidence that relations between the
two countries would enjoy sustainable development in future.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today Tang called on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. The
two sides exchanged views on Sino-Pak relations, regional issues
and other matters of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Sharif briefed Tang about the Pakistan-India talks and stressed
his commitment to seek resolutions of all outstanding issues with
India through dialogue and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that China was concerned about the Kashmir issue and
was sympathetic with the people of Kashmir and their sufferings.
</P>
<P>
Concluding his two-day visit to Pakistan, Tang left here for
Sri Lanka later this evening.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Killed, 20 Injured in Blast in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Three people were killed and 20
others seriously injured in a grenade blast in central Pakistan,
the official Associated Press of Pakistan reported Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred in a mosque in Multan, about 300 kilometers
south of Islamabad, earlier in the day when people were offering
prayers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that a hand grenade was thrown from outside in
the courtyard of the mosque, causing a two-inch deep and six-inch
wide crater on the floor.
</P>
<P>
Police reached the spot soon after being informed and the
injured were rushed to local hospitals, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
