<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Travel to Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said today that she will travel to the Middle
East at the end of the month provided progress is made in security
there.
</P>
<P>
"Provided there is some progress on security issues, I am
prepared to travel to the Middle East at the end of this month,"
Albright said in a speech at the National Press Club in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has come under pressure to continue
its active mediations between the Israelis and Palestinians as the
stalemate has been lingering for several months for the two sides
to come to the negotiating table on the Middle East peace process
and after last week's suicide bombings at a Jerusalem produce
market, which killed 15 people and injured more than 100.
</P>
<P>
U.S. mediator Dennis Ross will take a trip to the Middle East
this weekend in a hope to revitalize the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"We now face a crisis of confidence that has put at risk past
gains and rekindled old animosities," Albright said. "The sine qua
non is a mutual commitment to security against violence. This is
basic. This is common sense." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
