<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Bounces Back to Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip stocks bounced back
record highs today as bonds ended a brief slump, boosting
financial shares, and an alliance between Apple and Microsoft
added more fuel to the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 71.77 points to 8,259.31,
just topping last Wednesday's record close of 8,254.89.
</P>
<P>
Other major stock indicators also set new records, with the
technology-heavy Nasdaq market setting its sixth straight closing
high.
</P>
<P>
There was no big economic news to justify the day's strength,
but the bond market halted a three-session decline.
</P>
<P>
Most bellwether technology issues became active after Apple
Computer, which surged more than 6.5 U.S. dollars to 26.34 U.S.
dollars, announced a surprising alliance in which Microsoft will
invest 150 million U.S. dollars in the struggling computer maker.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a nearly 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was heavy
again at 565.22 million shares, more than 525.67 million in the
previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 7.95 to 960.32, and
the NYSE composite index rose 4.04 to 497.00, surpassing Thursday's
record highs by both measures.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.41 to 654.06,
and the Russell 2000 list of smaller companies rose 2.41 to 420.73,
the third straight record high for both measures.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.91 to 1,630.44, giving it a
3.7 percent gain during its six-session streak of record highs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
