<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 29 Apparently Survive in S.Korean Air Jet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers pulled charred bodies
today from the wreckage of a Korean Air jet that crashed in the
dense jungled hills near Guam's international airport and 29 of
the 254 people on board were found survived.
</P>
<P>
Flight 801, a Boeing 747, from Seoul, capital of South Korea,
went down five kilometers from its airport destination on the
U.S.-governed Pacific island at about 2:00 a.m. Wednesday local
time. It was carrying 231 passengers and 23 crew members when it
crashed in a driving rain.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers said they had found all the survivors 17 hours after
the crash. The exact number of survivors was unclear. Korean Air
said there were 29 survivors, including four flight attendants;
other unconfirmed reports said between 27 and 30 people survived.
</P>
<P>
The survivors had been seated in the front of the plane, which
was largely intact. But the plane's pilot and co-pilot were
missing and presumed dead, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-nine bodies had been recovered from the smoldering
wreckage by the time the rescue effort was called off for the
night, said Ginger Cruz, a spokeswoman for Guam Gov. Carl
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
"We scoured the whole area all day today," Air Force Col. Al
Riggle said. "We know there are some bodies still down there, but
it's smoldering too hot."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke by telephone with Guam's
governor to offer his own condolences, and the support of the
federal government as needed.
</P>
<P>
Rescue work was hampered because of rain-soaked sawgrass
covering the rocks that made it difficult to carry survivors.
Hundreds of rescuers had to make their way through mud and the
towering, razor-sharp sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
Two Navy CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters rescued survivors, many
of them burned. With the jet still smoldering, Navy Seabees moved
in backhoes to crack open the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
Korean Air planned to fly at least 300 relatives of victims and
survivors to Guam tonight. Airline vice-president Lee Tae-won said
a U.S. military transport plane will take some of the survivors
back to Seoul Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Boeing 747-300 delivered to Korean Air in 1984,
was trying to land at an airport that lacked both a main landing
system and a government-staffed control tower.
</P>
<P>
Some witnesses said they saw the plane was on fire or heard an
explosion before it went down to the ground. But one South Korean
survivor, Hong Hyon-sung, said there was no fire or explosion
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
Early reports quoted a White House official as saying that the
pilot reported fire before the accident. However, U.S. officials
later denied any report by the pilot.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board sent a team to
investigate the accident and the voice and flight-data recorders
have been found and sent to Washington for analysis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Positive About Peace Mechanism on Peninsula: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China is positive about the
establishment of a peace mechanism on the Korean Peninsula and
will adhere to this position in the four-party peace talks among
China, the United States, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) and South Korea, a spokesman for the Chinese delegation
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The four parties Tuesday kicked off an open-ended preparatory
session for the peace talks in Columbia Univercity's School of
International and Public Affairs in New York City.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has reportedly been focusing its discussions on
procedures of the four-party peace talks, including the date,
venue and agenda. The talks were proposed by U.S. President Bill
Clinton and South Korean President Kim Young Sam last April.
</P>
<P>
"China will act according to the principles of facilitating
peace and stability on the peninsula, work closely with the other
parties and make its efforts for progress in the talks and early
establishment of a peace mechanism," the spokesman said in a
briefing to the press.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that harsh reality has shown both in
the past and at present that continued tension on the peninsula
does not serve the interests of the people of the north or the
south of Korea, nor does it contribute to stability and peace in
Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that efforts must be made to change the situation
and find an effective way to long-term peace and stability," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed support for the reconciliation of the
south and north and improvement of relations between the DPRK and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that through sincere and candid consultations, a peace
mechanism will be put in place on the peninsula at an early date
and peaceful unification achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, we should not fail to see that given the
confrontation and hostility between the DPRK and the ROK and
between the DPRK and the US for decades, the parties concerned may
come up with some different views with regard to the operational
procedure of the peace talks and ways to establish a peace
mechanism," the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that the process leading to the establishment of a
peace mechanism on the peninsula is expected to be a long and
complicated one.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the talks calls for patience and unremitting
efforts from all parties," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Succeeds in Stabilizing Economy: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba said
here today that Zambia has succeeded in stabilizing its economy
and is now consolidating this stability.
</P>
<P>
Opening an international seminar whose theme being "From
Stabilization to Economic growth and Poverty Alleviation",
Chiluba said annual inflation rate of above 100 percent which had
persisted for a long time was brought to 35 percent in 1996 and
this year the rate is expected to be down further to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president stressed that a stable macro-economic
environment is a prerequisite for increased private sector
investment and sound economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, my government has long recognized that
sustained growth could only be possible once inflation has been
brought down under control," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Last year the economy grew by 6.4 percent and the gross
domestic product is projected to grow at 5.5 percent this year,
Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
The on-going privatization is aimed at scaling down
government's direct involvement in commercial activities and
reducing budgetary costs arising from subsidies to red-ink
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
It is also aimed at promoting competition and improving
efficiency of enterprises and stimulating both local and foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
On poverty reduction, the president said that the government
has been pursuing reforms that are focused on the devolution of
social safety measures to local authorities and the restructuring
of the water and sanitation sector.
</P>
<P>
He promised to continue to give priority to this sector in the
future budgets.
</P>
<P>
Local and foreign bankers, businessmen and representatives of
international organizations are attending the three-day seminar
to seek ways of promoting growth and reducing poverty in Zambia
and Africa as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian, Bosnian Leaders Reaffirm Commitment to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman and Chairman of the Bosnian Presidency Alija Izetbegovic
today reaffirmed their commitment to implementing the peace
agreements concerning Bosnia and the Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders along with their top aides met in Split,
Croatia, for the summit meeting which was delayed several times
due to strained relations that the Bosnian Muslims have had with
Croats and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued after the meeting said that meeting
dealt with the implementation of the Dayton peace agreement
concerning the whole Bosnia as well as the Washington agreement
concerning the Muslim-Croat federation and focused, "in
particular, on the strengthening of relations within the
federation... and its cooperation with the Republic of Croatia."
</P>
<P>
"The two sides confirmed readiness to conduct a consistent,
integral and accelerated implementation of the peace agreements
for the sake of strengthing peace and establishing and making
operational democratic institutions in Bosnia and Herzeovina, as
well as for the sake of the overall normalization of relations in
this part of Europe," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to expectations before the meeting, the leaders did
not sign any agreements but merely agreed that draft agreements on
a number of issues would be exchanged by September 1 and a joint
experts group would try to iron out differences in the following
three months.
</P>
<P>
The issues which require special attention are the use of
Ploce, which is a Croatian port but built with Bosnian investment
before the war, and transit through Neum, a Bosnian city which
cuts into the Croatian coastline, as well as property claims,
investment protection and dual citizenship, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, the two leaders met with a U.S. delegation
led by Assistant Secretary of State for Europe Robert Gelbard and
Richard Holbrooke, who brokered the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Split, Holbrooke said that the peace
process in Bosnia was moving "at much too slow a pace" and he and
hid fellow delegates were trying to "accelerate the process and
keep it moving forward." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Survey Shows Moderate Economic Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy is expanding
moderately in much of the nation, with prices remaining stable
despite tighter labor markets, a survey by the U.S. Federal
Reserve (Fed) said today.
</P>
<P>
"Economic activity generally expanded at a moderate rate in
many districts in June and July, although several reported that
growth was more brisk," the Fed survey of regional business
conditions said.
</P>
<P>
It said that labor markets tightened further, but only
scattered wage pressures were noted. "Prices for most goods were
stable, although reports indicated that lumber and some
agricultural prices rose."
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Fed's 12 district banks and known
as the beige book because of the color of its cover, will be used
by policy makers of the U.S. central bank when they meet on August
19 to consider monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Although the Fed's Open Market Committee met in May and July,
it has not raised short-term interest rates since it raised the
federal fund rate by a quarter of a percentage point to 5.5
percent on March 25.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government reported last week that the economic growth
slowed to an annual rate of 2.2 percent in the April-June quarter
following a strong 4.9 percent rate in the first quarter. But
analysts expect it to regain in the second half of the year some
of its first-quarter strength.
</P>
<P>
Few signs of substantial price hikes have emerged so far and
many analysts believe the U.S. Fed will leave rates unchanged for
now as it awaits more economic data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun-China Educational Ties Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Minister of Higher
Education Peter Tabi today spoke highly of the educational ties
between Cameroun and China while inaugurating the computer center
of the University of Yaounde.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony this morning at the university, Tabi
expressed gratitude to the Chinese government for donating the
dawning-1000 plus massively parallel processing (MPP) computer
system to the university which prompted the establishment of this
computer center.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the Cameroun-China cooperation in
higher education has made encouraging progress.
</P>
<P>
With the help of Chinese professors and technicians, he noted,
a micro-biological lab was set up at the University of Yaounde in
1991 and a Chinese language center established in the
International Institute of the University of Yaounde in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people are the sincere friends of Camerounians, Tabi
said, adding that they help Camerounians master technical
know-how.
</P>
<P>
Hui Yongzheng, vice minister of the state science and
technology commission of china, is currently visiting the country
as the head of the Chinese science and technology delegation.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese people would like to join hands with their
Camerounian friends in promoting the scientific and technological
development and encouraging the two nations' economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived here on Tuesday for a 24-hour
working visit at the invitation of Cameroun's Minister of Higher
Education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
