<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Teen-Agers Use More Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The use of heroin by U.S.
teen-agers is on the rise despite a slight decline in abuse of
marijuana, and the drug abuse rate is still much higher than it
was in 1992, a government report said today.
</P>
<P>
The annual National Household Survey on Drug Abuse released
today said 9 percent of U.S. teens used drugs in 1996, compared
with 10.9 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the survey also showed that drug use among 18 to 25 year
old young people increased from 13.3 percent in 1994 to 15.6
percent in 1996. And more teens tried heroin for the first time
last year than ever before.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, use of marijuana by teen-agers
declined very slightly from 8.2 percent to 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 22 percent of children aged 12-17 reported they had
used an illegal drug sometime during their lifetime and 48 percent
of young adults 18 to 25 had used some illegal drug. Over half of
Americans aged 26 to 34 have tried illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
The report said the rates of first use of heroin rose for both
those aged 12-17 and those aged 18-25 from 1990 to 1995. For
teen-agers, 2.5 percent reported first use of heroin in 1995, up
from 1.8 percent in 1994. For young adults, first use was reported
by 2.4 percent, up from 1.7 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Although marijuana use has dropped a bit, we remain concerned
that cocaine may be inching back up and heroin use is definitely
increasing," warned White House national drug policy director
Barry McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, 6.1 percent of the entire population used illegal
drugs in 1996, unchanged from 1995, but down from 14.1 percent in
1979.
</P>
<P>
The report also said there were 62 million American smokers of
all ages, representing 29 percent of the population. Teen tobacco
use remained flat at 18 percent, although use of smokeless tobacco
declined from 2.8 percent to 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
On alcohol, the report said about 9 million Americans under age
21 drank alcohol in 1996, including 4.4 million "binge drinkers,"
who had at least five drinks on one occasion in the last month.
There were 1.9 million heavy users, who binged at least five times
over the past month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970807.0322 </DOCNO>
